|696\n!PH-2\n|908\n|-\n!PH-3\n|40\n!PH-3\n|520\n!PH-3\n|754\n|}\n\n==List of Services==\n\nFollowing are the services which one gets on qualifying the Civil Service Examination.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.civilserviceindia.com/civil-services-list.html|title=UPSC Posts, Civil Services Posts, UPSC jobs List, Indian Civil Service, Indian Services Post|website=www.civilserviceindia.com|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref>\n\n'''All India Services'''\n* [[Indian Administrative Service]] ('''IAS''')\n* [[Indian Police Service]] ('''IPS''')\n*<!-- Do not add Indian Forest Service to this list as a seperate examination is conducted for that. Official Website for Indian Forest Services Exam : https://upsc.gov.in/examinations/Indian%20Forest%20Service%20%28Prel.%29%20Examination%202018%20through%20CS%28P%29%20Examination%2C%202018 -->\n\n'''Central Services (Group A)'''\n*[[Indian Foreign Service]] ('''IFS''')\n* [[Indian Audit and Accounts Service]] ('''IA&AS''')\n* [[Indian Civil Accounts Service]] ('''ICAS''')\n* [[Indian Corporate Law Service]] ('''ICLS''')\n* [[Indian Defence Accounts Service]] ('''IDAS''')\n* [[Indian Defence Estates Service]] ('''IDES''')\n* [[Indian Information Service]] ('''IIS''')\n* [[Indian Ordnance Factories Service]] ('''IOFS''')\n* [[Indian Postal Service]] ('''IPoS''')\n*[[Indian P&T Accounts and Finance Service]] ('''IP&TAFS''')\n* [[Indian Railway Accounts Service]] ('''IRAS''')\n* [[Indian Railway Personnel Service]] ('''IRPS''')\n* [[Railway Protection Force|Indian Railway Protection Force Service]] ('''IRPFS''')\n* [[Indian Railway Traffic Service]] ('''IRTS''')\n* [[Indian Revenue Service]] ('''IRS-IT''')\n* [[Indian Revenue Service]] ('''IRS-C&CE''')\n* [[Indian Trade Service]] ('''ITrS''')\n\n'''Group B Services'''\n* [[Armed Forces Headquarters Civil Services]] ('''AFHCS''')\n* [[Delhi, Andaman and Nicobar Islands Civil Service]] ('''DANICS''')\n* [[Delhi, Andaman and Nicobar Islands Police Service]] ('''DANIPS''')\n* Pondicherry Civil Service ('''PCS''')\n* Pondicherry Police Service ('''PPS''')\n\n==Preliminary==\nThe pattern of the Preliminary examination up to 2010 was based on the recommendations of the Kothari Commission (1979). It included two examinations, one on general studies worth 150 marks, and the second on one of 23 optional subjects worth 300 marks. Until 2011, when it was revamped,<ref name=pio>{{cite news|title=Change of pattern in UPSC |url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/345874/Change-of-pattern-in-UPSC.html |accessdate=10 July 2011 |newspaper=[[The Pioneer (Indian newspaper)|The Pioneer]] |date=22 June 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/604vtHWHW?url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/345874/Change-of-pattern-in-UPSC.html |archivedate=10 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the preliminary pattern was sustained with only minor changes once every ten to fifteen years.<ref name=pio/>\n\nFrom 2011 onwards, the preliminary examination intends to focus on analytical abilities and understanding rather than the ability to memorize. The new pattern includes two papers of two hours duration and 200 marks each.<ref name=ht>{{cite news|title=Changes in the civil service examination |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Changes-in-the-civil-service-examination/Article1-711918.aspx |accessdate=10 July 2011 |newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=21 June 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/604rj8vNB?url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Changes-in-the-civil-service-examination/Article1-711918.aspx |archivedate=10 July 2011 |location=[[New Delhi]] |url-status=dead }}</ref> Both papers have multiple choice objective type questions only.<ref name=ht/> They are as follows:\n* Paper I tests the candidate's knowledge on current events, history of India and Indian national movement, Indian and world geography, Indian polity panchayti Raj system and governance, economic and social development, environmental ecology, biodiversity, climate change and general science, Art and culture.<ref name=ht/>\n* Paper II (also called CSAT or Civil Services Aptitude Test), tests the candidate's skills in comprehension, interpersonal skills, communication, logical reasoning, analytical ability, decision making, problem solving, basic numeracy, data interpretation, English language comprehension skills and mental ability.<ref name=ht/> It is qualifying in nature and the marks obtained in this paper are not counted for merit. However, it is mandatory for the candidate to score a minimum of 33 per cent in this paper to qualify the Prelims exam.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.civilserviceindia.com/subject/preliminary-syllabus.html|title=UPSC Syllabus 2019, IAS Syllabus 2019, UPSC 2019 Syllabus, UPSC Prelims Syllabus, Csat Syllabus, IAS Prelims Syllabus, IAS Exam Prelims Syllabus|website=www.civilserviceindia.com|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, the Centre announced that English marks in CSAT will not be included for gradation or merit and 2011 candidates may get a second chance to appear for the test next year.<ref>{{cite news|title=CSAT Row : Marks of English paper will not be included for merit|url=http://www.patrika.com/news/csat-row-marks-of-english-paper-will-not-be-included-for-merit/1021728|accessdate=4 August 2014|work=Patrika Group|issue=4 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808022108/http://www.patrika.com/news/csat-row-marks-of-english-paper-will-not-be-included-for-merit/1021728|archive-date=8 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, the Government of India announced that Paper II of the preliminary examination will be qualifying in nature i.e. it will not be graded for eligibility in Mains Examination and a candidate will need to score at least 33% to be eligible for grading on the basis of marks of Paper I of the Preliminary Examination.<ref name=note/> Those who qualify in the Prelims become eligible for the Mains.\n\n==Mains==\nThe Civil Services Mains Examination consists of a written examination and an interview.<ref name=note/>\n\n===Examination===\nThe Civil Services Main written examination consists of nine papers, two qualifying and seven ranking in nature. The range of questions may vary from just one mark to sixty marks, twenty words to 600 words answers. Each paper is of a duration of 3 hours. Candidates who pass qualifying papers are ranked according to marks and a selected number of candidates are called for interview or a personality test at the Commission's discretion.\n\nAccording to the new marks allocations in Civil Service Examination 2013 there are some changes made in the examination according to the suggestion of the Prof. [[Arun Nigavekar|Arun. S. Nigavekar]] Committee.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=LiveMint|title=PM approves changes in civil services exam pattern|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/XiGXMdPHO44qm8728pHIBO/PM-approves-changes-in-civil-services-exam-pattern.html|accessdate=25 March 2013 |date=27 February 2013 }}</ref> However, after some controversy, the qualifying papers for Indian languages and English were restored.<ref>{{cite news|title=Govt rolls back changes to UPSC mains exam|newspaper=The Hindu|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/govt-rolls-back-changes-to-upsc-mains-exam/article4533535.ece?ref=relatedNews|date=2 September 2016|accessdate=31 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Civil Services New Mains Format<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iasplanner.com/civilservices/article/a-brief-introduction-to-civil-services-exam|title=A Brief introduction to Civil Services Exam {{!}} IAS Planner|website=www.iasplanner.com|access-date=2019-02-22}}</ref>\n|-\n! Paper !! Subject!!  Marks\n|-\n|Paper A||(One of the Indian languages listed below, to be selected by the candidate (from the languages listed in the [[Eighth Schedule to the Constitution of India]]) (Qualifying) ||300\n|-\n|Paper B||English (Qualifying) ||300\n|-\n|Paper I||Essay ||250\n|-\n|Paper II||General Studies I (Indian heritage and culture, history and geography of the world and society) ||250\n|-\n|Paper III||General Studies II (Governance, constitution, polity, social justice and international relations) ||250\n|-\n|Paper IV||General Studies III (Technology, economic development, bio-diversity, environment, security and disaster management) ||250\n|-\n|Paper V||General Studies IV (ethics, integrity and aptitude) ||250\n|-\n|Papers VI, VII||Two papers on one subject to be selected by the candidate from the list of optional subjects below (250 marks for each paper) ||500\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"| '''Sub Total (Written Test)''' || '''1750'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"| Personality Test (Interview) ||275\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"| '''Total Marks''' || '''2025'''\n|}\n\n==== List of languages ====\nThe examination is more than the following languages, with the name of the script in brackets:<ref name=2015notice>{{cite web |url= http://www.upsc.gov.in/exams/notifications/2015/CSP_2015/CSP_2015_eng.pdf |title= Civil Services Examination, 2015 |publisher=Union Public Services Commission |date= 23 May 2015 |access-date=23 June 2016 |page=5}}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Assamese language|Assamese]] ([[Assamese alphabet|Assamese]])\n* [[Bengali language|Bengali]] ([[Bengali alphabet|Bengali]])\n* [[Bodo language|Bodo]] ([[Devanagari]])\n* [[Dogri language|Dogri]] (Devanagari)\n* [[English language|English]] ([[English alphabet|English]])\n* [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] ([[Gujarati alphabet|Gujarati]])\n* [[Hindi]] (Devanagari)\n* [[Kannada]] ([[Kannada alphabet|Kannada]])\n* [[Kashmiri language|Kashmiri]] ([[Persian alphabet|Persian]])\n* [[Konkani language|Konkani]] (Devanagari)\n* [[Maithili language|Maithili]] (Devanagari)\n* [[Malayalam]] ([[Malayalam script|Malayalam]])\n* [[Meithei language|Manipuri]] (Bengali)\n* [[Marathi language|Marathi]] (Devanagari)\n* [[Nepali language|Nepali]] (Devanagari)\n* [[Odia language|Odia]] ([[Odia alphabet|Odia]])\n* [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] ([[Gurmukh\u012b alphabet|Gurumukhi]])\n* [[Sanskrit]] (Devanagari)\n* [[Santali language|Santhali]] (Devanagri or [[Ol Chiki alphabet|Ol Chiki]])\n* [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]] (Devanagari or [[Arabic alphabet|Arabic]])\n* [[Tamil language|Tamil]] ([[Tamil script|Tamil]])\n* [[Telugu language|Telugu]] ([[Telugu script|Telugu]])\n* [[Urdu]] (Persian)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==== Optional subjects ====\nThe subjects available for Papers VI and VII are:<ref name=2015notice/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nextias.com/optional-syllabus|title=UPSC Syllabus for Optional Subjects IAS 2019 Mains Optional Syllabus|website=www.nextias.com|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref> \n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Agriculture]]\n* [[Animal Husbandry]] and [[Veterinary Science]]\n* [[Anthropology]]\n* [[Botany]]\n* [[Chemistry]]\n* [[Civil Engineering]]\n* [[Commerce]] and [[Accountancy]]\n* [[Economics]]\n* [[Electrical Engineering]]\n* [[Geography]]\n* [[Geology]]\n* [[History]]\n* [[Law]]\n* [[Literature]] of any one of the languages listed above\n* [[Management]]\n* [[Mathematics]]\n* [[Mechanical Engineering]]\n* [[Medical Science]]\n* [[Philosophy]]\n* [[Physics]]\n* [[Political Science]] and [[International Relations]]\n* [[Psychology]]\n* [[Public Administration]]\n* [[Sociology]]\n* [[Statistics]]\n* [[Zoology]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== Interview ===\nOfficially called the \"Personality Test\", the objective of the interview is to assess the personal suitability of the candidate for a career in public service by a board of competent and unbiased observers. The test is intended to evaluate the mental calibre of a candidate. In broad terms, this is really an assessment of not only a candidate's intellectual qualities, but also social traits and interest in current affairs. Some of the qualities to be judged are mental alertness, critical powers of assimilation, clear and logical exposition, balance of judgement, variety and depth of interest, ability for social cohesion and leadership, and intellectual and moral integrity.\n\nThe technique of the interview is not that of a strict cross-examination, but of a natural, though directed and purposeful conversation that is intended to reveal the mental qualities of the candidate.\n\nThe interview is not intended to test either of the specialized or general knowledge of the candidate, which has been already tested through written papers. Candidates are expected to have taken an intelligent interest not only in their special subjects of academic study, but also in the events which are happening around them both within and outside their own state or country as well as in modern currents of thought and in new discoveries which should rouse the curiosity of all well-educated youth. The interview standards are very high and require thorough preparation as well as commitment.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.upsc.gov.in Union Public Service Commission official website]\n*[https://upsc.gov.in/examinations/Civil%20Services%20%28Preliminary%29%20Examination%2C%202019 Civil Services (Preliminary) Examination 2019 official website]\n*[https://upsc.gov.in/sites/default/files/Final_Notice_CSPE_2019_N.pdf Civil Services Examination 2019 official notification]\n\n{{Standardized tests in India}}\n\n[[Category:Standardised tests in India]]\n[[Category:Union Public Service Commission]]\n[[Category:Civil service tests in India]]\n", "name_user": "103.105.96.109", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eOptional subjects)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Civil_Services_Examination_(India)"}
{"title_page": "Geoffrey Darby", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian screenwriter|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Notability|bio|date=June 2016}}\n'''Geoffrey Darby''' is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[screenwriter]]. He worked on children's [[sketch comedy]] ''[[You Can't Do That on Television]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=So you Think ''You Can't do that on Television''|url=http://splitsider.com/2012/03/so-you-think-you-cant-do-that-on-television|last=Klickstein|first=Mathew|date=26 March 2012|work=Splitsider|access-date=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411202241/http://splitsider.com/2012/03/so-you-think-you-cant-do-that-on-television/|archive-date=11 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> for most of the show's run.\n\n==Career==\nDarby was the ''Double Dare'' host for the unaired pilot.<ref name=\"IMDb\">{{cite web|title = Geoffrey Darby|url = https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0200973/|website=IMDb|access-date=2 July 2016}}</ref> Some of Darby's other credits include the 1983 American sketch comedy TV show [[Don't Look Now (1983 TV series)|''Don't Look Now'']], the pilot episode ''[[UFO Kidnapped]]'', ''Clarissa Explains it All'', and ''Finders Keepers''.<ref name=\"IMDb\" />\n\nIn 1999 Darby was named President of Production for [[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen Media]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/geoffrey-darby-former-cbs-and-viacom-executive-named-president-of-production-for-oxygen-media-75358167.html|title=Geoffrey Darby, Former CBS and Viacom Executive, Named President of Production for Oxygen Media|publisher=Oxygen Media|type=Press release|via=PRNewswire|date=26 March 1999}}</ref> Darby is currently the executive vice president of programming at the [[The Weather Channel|Weather Channel]], taking the position in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=Geoffrey Darby named to TWC|url=http://www.theweathercompany.com/newsroom/2014/08/19/geoffrey-darby-named-executive-vice-president-programming-weather-channel|website=The Weather Company|type=Press release|date=5 March 2009|access-date=24 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Writing credits==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Production\n! Notes\n! Broadcaster\n|-\n|''[[You Can't Do That on Television]]''\n|\n*143 episodes (1979\u20131990)\n|[[Nickelodeon]]\n|-\n|''[[Don't Look Now (1983 TV series)|Don't Look Now]]''\n|\n*5 episodes (co-written with Roger Price, 1983)\n|[[PBS]]\n|-\n|''Whatever Turns You On''\n|\n*15 episodes (co-written with Roger Price, 1979)\n|Nickelodeon\n|-\n|''[[UFO Kidnapped]]''\n|\n*Feature film (co-written with Roger Price, 1983)\n|Nickelodeon\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{You Can't Do That On Television}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Darby, Geoffrey}}\n[[Category:Canadian male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian screenwriter|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Notability|bio|date=June 2016}}\n'''Geoffrey Darby''' is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[screenwriter]]. He worked on children's [[sketch comedy]] ''[[You Can't Do That on Television]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=So you Think ''You Can't do that on Television''|url=http://splitsider.com/2012/03/so-you-think-you-cant-do-that-on-television|last=Klickstein|first=Mathew|date=26 March 2012|work=Splitsider|access-date=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411202241/http://splitsider.com/2012/03/so-you-think-you-cant-do-that-on-television/|archive-date=11 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> for most of the show's run.\n\n==Career==\nDarby was the ''Double Dare'' host for the unaired pilot.<ref name=\"IMDb\">{{cite web|title = Geoffrey Darby|url = https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0200973/|website=IMDb|access-date=2 July 2016}}</ref> Some of Darby's other credits include the 1983 American sketch comedy TV show [[Don't Look Now (1983 TV series)|''Don't Look Now'']], the pilot episode ''[[UFO Kidnapped]]'', ''Clarissa Explains it All'', and ''Finders Keepers''.<ref name=\"IMDb\" />\n\nIn 1999 Darby was named President of Production for [[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen Media]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/geoffrey-darby-former-cbs-and-viacom-executive-named-president-of-production-for-oxygen-media-75358167.html|title=Geoffrey Darby, Former CBS and Viacom Executive, Named President of Production for Oxygen Media|publisher=Oxygen Media|type=Press release|via=PRNewswire|date=26 March 1999}}</ref> Darby is currently the executive vice president of programming at the [[The Weather Channel|Weather Channel]], taking the position in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=Geoffrey Darby named to TWC|url=http://www.theweathercompany.com/newsroom/2014/08/19/geoffrey-darby-named-executive-vice-president-programming-weather-channel|website=The Weather Company|type=Press release|date=5 March 2009|access-date=24 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Writing credits==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Production\n! Notes\n! Broadcaster\n|-\n|''[[You Can't Do That on Television]]''\n|\n*143 episodes (1979\u20131990)\n|[[Nickelodeon]]\n|-\n|''[[Don't Look Now (1983 TV series)|Don't Look Now]]''\n|\n*5 episodes (co-written with Roger Price, 1983)\n|[[PBS]]\n|-\n|''Whatever Turns You On''\n|\n*15 episodes (co-written with Roger Price, 1979)\n|Nickelodeon\n|-\n|''[[UFO Kidnapped]]''\n|\n*Feature film (co-written with Roger Price, 1983)\n|Nickelodeon\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{You Can't Do That On Television}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Darby, Geoffrey}}\n[[Category:Canadian male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geoffrey_Darby"}
{"title_page": "Wezenberg Olympic Swimming Center", "text_new": "The '''Wezenberg Olympic Swimming Center''' is a swimming center with a 50-meter pool located on De Singel in [[Antwerp]]. The complex dates from 1973. In addition to the Olympic-size swimming pool, there is an instruction pool of 20 by 17 meters in Wezenberg and since 2015 a second 50-meter pool, not wide enough for competitions, but for training.\n\n== History ==\nIn 1920 there was already an Olympic outdoor swimming pool on the Wezenberg. It was the location for Swimming at the [[1920 Summer Olympics]]. In 1951, a new outdoor swimming pool was opened and used for years before work on the indoor swimming pool started in the 1970s. The new swimming pool was opened in 1973.\n\nFrom September 2014 to September 2015, a second Olympic pool was built at 8 m from the existing pool, Wezenberg 2, with six swimming lanes that will not be open to the public, but will be used as a training pool for top athletes. This pool will be expanded with a high-tech equipment for image and time registration. Wezenberg 2 is 50.025 m long, 16 meters wide and 2.2 m deep. The construction of Wezenberg 2 cost 8 million euros, of which 4.5 million by the City of Antwerp and 3.5 million by the Flemish government. The trainings in the new bath were possible from October 1, 2015, the opening took place on November 27, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gva.be/cnt/dmf20150831_01841872/zwembad-wezenberg-2-vullen-zal-week-duren |title=Zwembad Wezenberg 2 vullen zal week duren |language=nl |publisher=[[Gazet van Antwerpen]] |date=31 August 2015 |access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n\nThe swimming center is the home base of Swimming club Brabo with Pieter Timmers and Kimberly Buys, among others. In Wezenberg, the provincial championships are also organized every year, as well as the international club competition Antwerp International Youth Swimming Cup. The Belgian championships are held regularly in the swimming pool, such as the BK 2010. In the summer of 2012, the European Junior Championships took place for the fourth time, previously this also happened in 1991, 1998 and 2007. In 2001, the European Championships short swimming championships organized.\n\nThe total area is 7,500 m\u00b2. The stands have 800 seats. Renovations took place in 2001\u20132002, 2011 and 2015, among which work by Beno\u00eet van Innis was applied to wall tiles.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [[:nl:Olympisch zwemcentrum Wezenberg?key=3|Original Wikipedia Dutch language article]]\n\n{{coord|51.192761|4.406371|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Swimming venues in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Antwerp]]\n[[Category:Sport in Antwerp]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Wezenberg Olympic Swimming Center''' is a swimming center with a 50-meter pool located on De Singel in [[Antwerp]]. The complex dates from 1973.\n\nIn addition to the Olympic-size swimming pool, there is an instruction pool of 20 by 17 meters in Wezenberg and since 2015 a second 50-meter pool, not wide enough for competitions, but for training.\n\n== History ==\nIn 1920 there was already an Olympic outdoor swimming pool on the Wezenberg. It was the location for Swimming at the [[1920 Summer Olympics]]. In 1951, a new outdoor swimming pool was opened and used for years before work on the indoor swimming pool started in the 1970s. The new swimming pool was opened in 1973.\n\nFrom September 2014 to September 2015, a second Olympic pool was built at 8 m from the existing pool, Wezenberg 2, with six swimming lanes that will not be open to the public, but will be used as a training pool for top athletes. This pool will be expanded with a high-tech equipment for image and time registration. Wezenberg 2 is 50.025 m long, 16 meters wide and 2.2 m deep. The construction of Wezenberg 2 cost 8 million euros, of which 4.5 million by the City of Antwerp and 3.5 million by the Flemish government. The trainings in the new bath were possible from October 1, 2015, the opening took place on November 27, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gva.be/cnt/dmf20150831_01841872/zwembad-wezenberg-2-vullen-zal-week-duren |title=Zwembad Wezenberg 2 vullen zal week duren |language=nl |publisher=[[Gazet van Antwerpen]] |date=31 August 2015 |access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n\nThe swimming center is the home base of Swimming club Brabo with Pieter Timmers and Kimberly Buys, among others. In Wezenberg, the provincial championships are also organized every year, as well as the international club competition Antwerp International Youth Swimming Cup. The Belgian championships are held regularly in the swimming pool, such as the BK 2010. In the summer of 2012, the European Junior Championships took place for the fourth time, previously this also happened in 1991, 1998 and 2007. In 2001, the European Championships short swimming championships organized.\n\nThe total area is 7,500 m\u00b2. The stands have 800 seats. Renovations took place in 2001\u20132002, 2011 and 2015, among which work by Beno\u00eet van Innis was applied to wall tiles.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [[:nl:Olympisch zwemcentrum Wezenberg?key=3|Original Wikipedia Dutch language article]]\n\n{{coord|51.192761|4.406371|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Swimming venues in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Antwerp]]\n[[Category:Sport in Antwerp]]\n", "name_user": "Doomsdayer520", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wezenberg_Olympic_Swimming_Center"}
{"title_page": "Paradise Postponed", "text_new": "{{italic title}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2014}}\n\n{{infobox television \n | show_name = Paradise Postponed\n | image = File:ParadisePostponedNovel.jpg\n | image_size = 200\n | caption = Novel on which series is based<br>(publ. [[Viking Press]])\n | writer = [[John Mortimer]]\n | director = [[Alvin Rakoff]]\n | producer = \n | starring = [[Michael Hordern]] <br> [[Annette Crosbie]] <br> [[Peter Egan]]<br> [[Paul Shelley]]<br>[[David Threlfall]]\n | country = United Kingdom\n | language = English\n | company = [[Thames Television]]\n | network = [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n | first_aired = {{Start date|1986|9|15|df=y}}\n | last_aired = {{End date|1986|11|24|df=y}}\n | audio_format = [[Monaural|Mono]]\n | picture_format = [[4:3]]\n | num_series = 1\n | num_episodes = 11\n | runtime = 50 minutes\n | list_episodes = \n | related = \n}}\n\n'''''Paradise Postponed''''' (1986) is a British 11-episode TV serial based on a novel by writer [[John Mortimer]]. He had adapted ''[[Brideshead Revisited]]'' as a television series and wrote ''[[Rumpole of the Bailey]].'' The series covered a span of 30 years of postwar British history, set in a small village.\n\n==Plot==\nThe series explores the mystery of why Reverend Simeon Simcox, a \"wealthy Socialist rector\", bequeathed the millions of the Simcox brewery estate to Leslie Titmuss, a city developer and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] cabinet minister.<ref name=\"nyt\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1986/10/17/arts/tv-weekend-paradise-postponed-a-new-series-on-masterpiece-theater.html JOHN J. O'CONNOR, \"TV WEEKEND; 'PARADISE POSTPONED,' A NEW SERIES ON 'MASTERPIECE THEATER' \"], ''New York Times,'' 17 October 1986, accessed 29 February 2016</ref> Simeon's sons Fred, a jazz-drumming country doctor, and Henry, once Britain's brightest and angriest writer who now works for Hollywood, conduct inquiries into their father's life as they try to understand the will. The setting of the work in an English village shows it absorbing and reflecting the upheavals of British society from the 1940s to the 1970s, and the many changes of the post-World War II society.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Michael Hordern]] - Rev. Simeon Simcox\n* [[Annette Crosbie]] - Dorothy Simcox\n* [[Peter Egan]] -  Henry Simcox\n* [[Paul Shelley]] - Fred Simcox\n* [[Colin Blakely]] - Dr. Salter\n* [[Eleanor David]] - Agnes Simcox, n\u00e9e Salter\n* [[Jill Bennett (British actress)|Jill Bennett]] - Lady Grace Fanner\n* [[Richard Vernon]] - Sir Nicholas Fanner\n* [[Zo\u00eb Wanamaker]] - Charlotte 'Charlie' Titmuss, n\u00e9e Fanner\n* [[David Threlfall]] - Leslie Titmuss\n* [[Colin Jeavons]] - George Titmuss\n* [[Albert Welling]] - Rev. Kevin Bulstrode\n* [[Harold Innocent]] - Jackson Catelow\n* [[Thomas Heathcote]] - Tom Nowt\n* [[Claire Oberman]] - Lonnie Simcox, n\u00e9e Hope\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nThe TV series was directed by [[Alvin Rakoff]] and was mainly shot in [[Henley-on-Thames]] and [[Marlow, Buckinghamshire]] in the second half of 1985. A three-part sequel, entitled ''[[Titmuss Regained]]'', aired in 1991.\n\n==Reception==\nThe ''New York Times'' described the series as a \"decided disappointment,\" with Mortimer having perhaps taken on too much.<ref name=\"nyt\"/> The technique of time shifts from the present to near past is said to be confusing more than illuminating of its characters.<ref name=\"nyt\"/> While containing a \"distinct whiff of snobbery\", the character of the lower-class Leslie Titmuss who rises on his wiles is developed as the most fascinating figure in the cast.<ref name=\"nyt\"/> In a 2014 retrospective review, Toby Manning of ''[[The Guardian]]'' called the series \"beautifully acted\", \"simply oozes nostalgia for a bygone Britain\" and called the character Titmuss \"quite simply one of the most compelling characters in TV history.\"<ref name=\"tg\">[https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/feb/27/paradise-postponed-box-set-review Toby Manning, \"Paradise Postponed box-set review\"], ''The Guardian,'' 27 February 2014, accessed 6 April 2019</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0090499}}\n* {{epguides|ParadisePostponed}}\n* {{tv.com show|paradise-postponed}}\n* [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,960952,00.html Review of Mortimer's novel], ''Time'' magazine (1986)]\n* [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A0DE7D6123DF934A25753C1A960948260 Review of the TV series], ''The New York Times'' (1986)]\n{{John Mortimer}}\n\n[[Category:1986 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1986 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:1980s British drama television series]]\n[[Category:1980s British television miniseries]]\n[[Category:ITV television dramas]]\n[[Category:Television programmes based on British novels]]\n[[Category:Period television series]]\n[[Category:Works by John Mortimer]]\n[[Category:Television programmes produced by Thames Television]]\n[[Category:Television series by Euston Films]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series about Christian religious leaders]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2014}}\n\n{{infobox television \n | show_name = Paradise Postponed\n | image = File:ParadisePostponedNovel.jpg\n | image_size = 200\n | caption = Novel on which series is based<br>(publ. [[Viking Press]])\n | writer = [[John Mortimer]]\n | director = [[Alvin Rakoff]]\n | producer = \n | starring = [[Michael Hordern]] <br> [[Annette Crosbie]] <br> [[Peter Egan]]<br> [[Paul Shelley]]<br>[[David Threlfall]]\n | country = United Kingdom\n | language = English\n | company = [[Thames Television]]\n | network = [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n | first_aired = {{Start date|1986|9|15|df=y}}\n | last_aired = {{End date|1986|11|24|df=y}}\n | audio_format = [[Monaural|Mono]]\n | picture_format = [[4:3]]\n | num_series = 1\n | num_episodes = 11\n | runtime = 50 minutes\n | list_episodes = \n | related = \n}}\n\n'''''Paradise Postponed''''' (1986) is a British 11-episode TV serial based on a novel by writer [[John Mortimer]]. He had adapted ''[[Brideshead Revisited]]'' as a television series and wrote ''[[Rumpole of the Bailey]].'' The series covered a span of 30 years of postwar British history, set in a small village.\n\n==Plot==\nThe series explores the mystery of why Reverend Simeon Simcox, a \"wealthy Socialist rector\", bequeathed the millions of the Simcox brewery estate to Leslie Titmuss, a city developer and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] cabinet minister.<ref name=\"nyt\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1986/10/17/arts/tv-weekend-paradise-postponed-a-new-series-on-masterpiece-theater.html JOHN J. O'CONNOR, \"TV WEEKEND; 'PARADISE POSTPONED,' A NEW SERIES ON 'MASTERPIECE THEATER' \"], ''New York Times,'' 17 October 1986, accessed 29 February 2016</ref> Simeon's sons Fred, a jazz-drumming country doctor and Henry, once Britain's brightest and angriest writer who now works for Hollywood, conduct inquiries into their father's life as they try to understand the will. The setting of the work in an English village, shows it absorbing and reflecting the upheavals of British society from the 1940s to the 1970s, the many changes of the post-World War II society.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Michael Hordern]] - Rev. Simeon Simcox\n* [[Annette Crosbie]] - Dorothy Simcox\n* [[Peter Egan]] -  Henry Simcox\n* [[Paul Shelley]] - Fred Simcox\n* [[Colin Blakely]] - Dr. Salter\n* [[Eleanor David]] - Agnes Simcox, n\u00e9e Salter\n* [[Jill Bennett (British actress)|Jill Bennett]] - Lady Grace Fanner\n* [[Richard Vernon]] - Sir Nicholas Fanner\n* [[Zo\u00eb Wanamaker]] - Charlotte 'Charlie' Titmuss, n\u00e9e Fanner\n* [[David Threlfall]] - Leslie Titmuss\n* [[Colin Jeavons]] - George Titmuss\n* [[Albert Welling]] - Rev. Kevin Bulstrode\n* [[Harold Innocent]] - Jackson Catelow\n* [[Thomas Heathcote]] - Tom Nowt\n* [[Claire Oberman]] - Lonnie Simcox, n\u00e9e Hope\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nThe TV series was directed by [[Alvin Rakoff]] and was mainly shot in [[Henley-on-Thames]] and [[Marlow, Buckinghamshire]] in the second half of 1985. A three-part sequel, entitled ''[[Titmuss Regained]]'', aired in 1991.\n\n==Reception==\nThe ''New York Times'' described the series as a \"decided disappointment,\" with Mortimer having perhaps taken on too much.<ref name=\"nyt\"/> The technique of time shifts from the present to near past is said to be confusing more than illuminating of its characters.<ref name=\"nyt\"/> While containing a \"distinct whiff of snobbery\", the character of the lower-class Leslie Titmuss who rises on his wiles is developed as the most fascinating figure in the cast.<ref name=\"nyt\"/> In a 2014 retrospective review, Toby Manning of ''[[The Guardian]]'' called the series \"beautifully acted\", \"simply oozes nostalgia for a bygone Britain\" and called the character Titmuss \"quite simply one of the most compelling characters in TV history.\"<ref name=\"tg\">[https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/feb/27/paradise-postponed-box-set-review Toby Manning, \"Paradise Postponed box-set review\"], ''The Guardian,'' 27 February 2014, accessed 6 April 2019</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0090499}}\n* {{epguides|ParadisePostponed}}\n* {{tv.com show|paradise-postponed}}\n* [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,960952,00.html Review of Mortimer's novel], ''Time'' magazine (1986)]\n* [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A0DE7D6123DF934A25753C1A960948260 Review of the TV series], ''The New York Times'' (1986)]\n{{John Mortimer}}\n\n[[Category:1986 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1986 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:1980s British drama television series]]\n[[Category:1980s British television miniseries]]\n[[Category:ITV television dramas]]\n[[Category:Television programmes based on British novels]]\n[[Category:Period television series]]\n[[Category:Works by John Mortimer]]\n[[Category:Television programmes produced by Thames Television]]\n[[Category:Television series by Euston Films]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series about Christian religious leaders]]\n", "name_user": "Marpool Man", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paradise_Postponed"}
{"title_page": "Murray Pittock", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n'''Murray G. H. Pittock''' FRSE<ref>{{cite web|title=Murray Bio|url=http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/p/23867/Murray+PITTOCK.aspx|publisher=Debretts.com|accessdate=2 January 2014}}</ref> (born 5 January 1962) is a Scottish historian, Bradley Professor of Literature at the [[University of Glasgow]] and Pro Vice Principal at the University, where he has served in senior roles including Dean and Vice Principal since 2008. He is currently engaged in leading on the Kelvin Hall development (kelvinhall.org.uk), the first phase of which was opened by the First Minister, Nicola Sturgeon, and with other major projects on learning and teaching space and Glasgow's unique early career development programme.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gla.ac.uk/myglasgow/news/headline_678549_en.html|title=Early Career Development Programme celebrates its successes|website=www.gla.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> He has also acted as lead or co-lead for a range of national and International partnerships, including with the Smithsonian Institution <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gla.ac.uk/explore/glasgowinternational/uofginternational/headline_607683_en.html|title=University welcome for Provost of the Smithsonian|website=www.gla.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>, and plays a leading role in the University's engagement with government and the cultural and creative industries (CCIs), organizing the 'Glasgow and Dublin: Creative Cities' summit in the British Embassy in Dublin in 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gla.ac.uk/schools/cca/news/headline_647168_en.html|title=Dublin and Glasgow: Creative Cities Summit|website=www.gla.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> He also produced a major report on the impact of Robert Burns on the Scottish Economy for the Scottish Government in 2020; a Parliamentary debate was held at Holyrood on the recommendations. <ref>{{Citation|last=TV|first=Scottish Parliament|title=Members' Business: Robert Burns in the Scottish Economy|url=https://www.scottishparliament.tv/meeting/members-business-robert-burns-in-the-scottish-economy-january-21-2020|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>Outside the University, he serves on the Research Excellence Framework (REF) Institutional Environment Pilot Panel<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gla.ac.uk/myglasgow/news/peopleprojects/headline_625564_en.html|title=Murray Pittock appointed to REF 2021 Institutional Environment Pilot Panel|website=www.gla.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>, and the National Trust for Scotland Board<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nts.org.uk/our-people/trustees-and-governance|title=Trustees and Governance|last=Scotland|first=National Trust for|date=2020-04-14|website=National Trust for Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>. He also serves as Scottish History Adviser to the NTS and as an adviser to a wide range of other national heritage bodies. He is President of the Edinburgh Walter Scott Club in 2019-20 and 2021-22.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.walterscottclub.com/2019-murray-pittock|title=2019 Murray Pittock|website=The Edinburgh Sir Walter Scott Club|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nPreviously he was Professor of Scottish and Romantic Literature and Deputy Head of Arts at the [[University of Manchester]], becoming the first ever professor of Scottish Literature at an English university. He has also held visiting appointments at universities worldwide in Celtic Studies, English, History, Languages and Equality and Diversity including: [[New York University]] (2015), [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]] (2014), [[Charles University]], Prague (2010); [[Trinity College, Dublin|Trinity College]], Dublin (2008); Auburn (2006) the [[University of Wales]] in advanced Welsh and Celtic studies (2002) and [[Yale]] (1998, 2000\u201301). <ref>{{cite web|title=Professor Murray Pittock|url=http://www.gla.ac.uk/schools/critical/staff/murraypittock/|publisher=University of Glasgow|accessdate=2 January 2014}}</ref> He has been invited as a visitor or to speak at half the world's leading universities, including Berkeley, Columbia, Harvard, Stanford and the Sorbonne.\n\n\n\n==Biography==\nMurray Pittock was born to Malcolm Pittock and Joan MacCormack. He grew up in [[Aberdeen]], attended [[Aberdeen Grammar School]], and studied at [[University of Glasgow]] aged 16. \n\n==Education and academia==\nPittock received an M.A. from the [[University of Glasgow]], then won the [[Snell Exhibition]] to study at [[Balliol College]], [[Oxford]] where he completed his [[Doctor of Philosophy|D.Phil]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Balliol College Archives & Manuscripts|url=http://archives.balliol.ox.ac.uk/History/snellexh.asp|publisher=University of Oxford|accessdate=2 January 2014}}</ref> At Balliol he was (with [[Boris Johnson]]) Oxford University Debating Champion and a member of the [[British Isles Debating Team]]/ESU-USA Tour. He ran the Express Newspapers Scottish national debating competition in 1982\u201383 and has had a long media career with over 1600 appearances in some 50 countries. In 2014 he was described as 'Scotland's leading public intellectual'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gla.ac.uk/colleges/arts/knowledge-exchange/themes/writingandpublishing/#/theroadtoindependence|title=University of Glasgow \u2013 Colleges \u2013 College of Arts \u2013 Industry Engagement \u2013 Industry Sectors \u2013 Writing and Publishing|publisher=University of Glasgow|access-date=23 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nPittock was appointed as a lecturer and then, [[reader (academic rank)|reader]], at the [[University of Edinburgh]] in 1989 and 1994, where he also had Faculty and University roles, including the corporate policy lead for the University's Scotland-related policies. He moved to [[Glasgow]] in 1996 to take up a chair in Literature at the [[University of Strathclyde]], also serving as Head of Department, a member of the Governing Body and theme lead for Arts, Culture and Sport policy. In 2003 Pittock moved to the [[University of Manchester]] as Professor of Scottish and Romantic Literature and worked on the changes needed for the merger with UMIST in Arts. He moved to Glasgow in 2007.\n\n==Academic work==\nPittock's books deal with a variety of subjects including [[English studies|English]], History, [[Irish Studies]], Theology and Politics. His research includes groundbreaking books on the Jacobite literature and the Jacobite armies, and on the nature of national culture, the construction of Celtic identities and the existence and nature of a distinctive Scottish Romanticism. His work has appeared in Braille, Hebrew, Mandarin and Spanish as well as in English  His study of Culloden was chosen as one of the ten best history books of the year by ''History Today''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.historytoday.com/history-today/best-history-books-2016|title=The best history books of 2016 {{!}} History Today|website=www.historytoday.com|access-date=23 March 2017}}</ref> and was recommended by Conservative MP Keith Simpson for reading by all non-Scottish MPs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gla.ac.uk/myglasgow/news/headline_500575_en.html|title=University of Glasgow \u2013 MyGlasgow \u2013 Campus e-News \u2013 Culloden study named in 2016 top ten|publisher=University of Glasgow|access-date=23 March 2017}}</ref>  In 2018, Pittock published the first ever scholarly edition of Robert Burns and James Johnson's Scots Musical Museum in two volumes and a book which challenges the conventional dates for the Enlightenment and uses Smart City theory to explore the early modern city. He is currently working on The Global History of Scotland for Yale and acting as General Editor of the Edinburgh Edition of Allan Ramsay, which received a major Arts and Humanities Research Council grant for 2018-23.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gla.ac.uk/schools/critical/research/researchcentresandnetworks/robertburnsstudies/edinburghenlightenment/theeditorialteam/|title=University of Glasgow - Schools - School of Critical Studies - Research - Research Centres and Networks - Centre for Robert Burns Studies - The Collected Works of Allan Ramsay - The Editorial Team|website=www.gla.ac.uk|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> In 2013,  he planned and secured agreement for the development of a national graduate school of arts and humanities in Scotland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abdn.ac.uk/news/4908/|title=Scottish universities awarded \u00a314.2m for arts & humanities doctoral training initiative {{!}} News {{!}} The University of Aberdeen|website=www.abdn.ac.uk|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> In 2014, he founded the first International Association for the Study of Scottish Literatures, which has held or is planning a sequence of international Congresses, at Glasgow (2014), Vancouver (2017), Prague (2021), Nottingham (2023) and Columbia SC (2026).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/opinion/columnists/scottish-literature-has-global-audience-1531326|title=Scottish literature has global audience|website=www.scotsman.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> \n\n==Honors==\nPittock is also a fellow of the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]] (2004) and has been awarded or shortlisted for numerous prizes. He is one of few academics to have given a prize lecture at both the Royal Society of Edinburgh and the [[British Academy]], where he gave the Chatterton lecture in poetry in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chatterton Lectures on Poetry|url=http://www.britac.ac.uk/lectures/chatterton.cfm|publisher=Britac.ac.uk|accessdate=2 January 2014}}</ref> In 2011\u201313, he also convened the National Champions' Group, supporting the introduction and development of [[Scottish Studies]] in schools.<ref>{{cite web|last=Denholm|first=Andrew|title=Call for our politicians to unite on Scottish studies|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/education/call-for-our-politicians-to-unite-on-scottish-studies.17048256|work=The Herald|location=Glasgow|accessdate=2 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n*''Enlightenment in a Smart City: Edinburgh's Civic Development, 1660-1750 (2018)''\n*''The Scots Musical Museum\" (2 vols: 2018)''\n*' ''<nowiki/>'Culloden (2016)''\n* ''The Reception of Robert Burns in Europe'' (ed, 2014)\n* ''The Road to Independence ? Scotland in the Balance'' (2014)\n* ''Material Culture and Sedition'' (2013)\n* ''The Edinburgh Companion to Scottish Romanticism'' (ed, 2011) \n* ''Robert Burns in Global Culture'' (ed, 2011) \n* ''Loyalty and Identity'' (co-ed, 2010)\n* ''The Myth of the Jacobite Clans: The Jacobite Army in 1745'' (2009) \n* ''Scottish and Irish Romanticism'' (2008, corrected ed, 2011) \n* ''The Road to Independence? Scotland Since the Sixties'' (2008)\n* ''James Boswell'' (2007)\n* ''The Reception of Sir Walter Scott in Europe'' (ed, 2007; corrected ed, 2014)\n* ''The Edinburgh History of Scottish Literature'' (co-ed, 2006)\n* ''A New History of Scotland'' (2003)\n* ''James Hogg: The Jacobite Relics of Scotland'', 2 volumes, (2002\u201303)\n* ''Scottish Nationality'' (2001)\n* ''Celtic Identity and the British Image'' (1999)\n* ''Jacobitism'' (1998)\n* ''Inventing and Resisting Britain'' (1997)\n* ''The Myth of the Jacobite Clans'' (1995)\n* ''Poetry and Jacobite Politics in Eighteenth-Century Britain and Ireland'' (1994; paperback, 2006)\n* ''Spectrum of Decadence: The Literature of the 1890s'' (1993,reissued 2014, paperback 2016)\n* ''Clio's Clavers'' (1992)\n* ''The Invention of Scotland'' (1991, reissued 2014, paperback 2016)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.gla.ac.uk/schools/critical/research/researchcentresandnetworks/robertburnsstudies/edinburghenlightenment/ Centre for Robert Burns Studies]\n* [https://ora.ox.ac.uk/objects/uuid:6fa01d5c-e900-4ee8-9fb6-a8c3645e0bdd Full text of doctoral thesis, \"Decadence and the English tradition\"] via Oxford Research Archive\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pittock, Murray}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish historians]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n'''Murray G. H. Pittock''' FRSE<ref>{{cite web|title=Murray Bio|url=http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/p/23867/Murray+PITTOCK.aspx|publisher=Debretts.com|accessdate=2 January 2014}}</ref> (born 5 January 1962) is a British cultural historian, Bradley Professor of Literature at the [[University of Glasgow]] and Pro Vice Principal at the University, where he was previously Vice Principal, Head of the College of Arts and Dean from 2009 to 2015. He is currently engaged in leading on the Kelvin Hall development (kelvinhall.org.uk), the first phase of which was opened by the First Minister, Nicola Sturgeon, on 11 November 2016 and with other major projects on learning and teaching space and Glasgow's unique early career development programme.\n\nPreviously he was Professor of Scottish and Romantic Literature and Deputy Head of Arts at the [[University of Manchester]], becoming the first ever professor of Scottish Literature at an English university. He has also held visiting appointments at universities worldwide in Celtic Studies, English, History, Languages and Equality and Diversity including: [[New York University]] (2015), [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]] (2014), [[Charles University]], Prague (2010); [[Trinity College, Dublin|Trinity College]], Dublin (2008); Auburn (2006) the [[University of Wales]] in advanced Welsh and Celtic studies (2002) and [[Yale]] (1998, 2000\u201301).<ref>{{cite web|title=Professor Murray Pittock|url=http://www.gla.ac.uk/schools/critical/staff/murraypittock/|publisher=University of Glasgow|accessdate=2 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n\n==Biography==\nMurray Pittock was born to Malcolm Pittock and Joan MacCormack. He grew up in [[Aberdeen]], attended [[Aberdeen Grammar School]], and studied at [[University of Glasgow]] aged 16. \n\n==Education and academia==\nPittock received an M.A. from the [[University of Glasgow]], then won the [[Snell Exhibition]] to study at [[Balliol College]], [[Oxford]] where he completed his [[Doctor of Philosophy|D.Phil]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Balliol College Archives & Manuscripts|url=http://archives.balliol.ox.ac.uk/History/snellexh.asp|publisher=University of Oxford|accessdate=2 January 2014}}</ref> At Balliol he was (with [[Boris Johnson]]) Oxford University Debating Champion and a member of the [[British Isles Debating Team]]/ESU-USA Tour. He ran the Express Newspapers Scottish national debating competition in 1982\u201383 and has had a long media career with over 1600 appearances in some 50 countries. In 2014 he was described as 'Scotland's leading public intellectual'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gla.ac.uk/colleges/arts/knowledge-exchange/themes/writingandpublishing/#/theroadtoindependence|title=University of Glasgow \u2013 Colleges \u2013 College of Arts \u2013 Industry Engagement \u2013 Industry Sectors \u2013 Writing and Publishing|publisher=University of Glasgow|access-date=23 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nPittock was appointed as a lecturer and then, [[reader (academic rank)|reader]], at the [[University of Edinburgh]] in 1989 and 1994, where he also had Faculty and University roles, including the corporate policy lead for the University's Scotland-related policies. He moved to [[Glasgow]] in 1996 to take up a chair in Literature at the [[University of Strathclyde]], also serving as Head of Department, a member of the Governing Body and theme lead for Arts, Culture and Sport policy. In 2003 Pittock moved to the [[University of Manchester]] as Professor of Scottish and Romantic Literature and worked on the changes needed for the merger with UMIST in Arts. He moved to Glasgow in 2007.\n\n==Academic work==\nPittock's books deal with a variety of subjects including [[English studies|English]], History, [[Irish Studies]], Theology and Politics. \nHowever he is best-known for writing on Scotland, and has spoken widely on identity and independence. His book, ''The Road to Independence? Scotland Since the Sixties'', was launched in [[Catalan language|Catalan]] with [[Scotland]]'s [[First Minister]], [[Alex Salmond]], in [[Port Olympic]], Barcelona in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Independently Minded? A Conversation with Murray Pittock|url=http://wp.iamone.co.uk/?p=381|publisher=Wp.iamone.co.uk|accessdate=2 January 2014}}</ref> His study of Culloden was chosen as one of the ten best history books of the year by ''History Today''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.historytoday.com/history-today/best-history-books-2016|title=The best history books of 2016 {{!}} History Today|website=www.historytoday.com|access-date=23 March 2017}}</ref> and was recommended by Conservative MP Keith Simpson for reading by all non-Scottish MPs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gla.ac.uk/myglasgow/news/headline_500575_en.html|title=University of Glasgow \u2013 MyGlasgow \u2013 Campus e-News \u2013 Culloden study named in 2016 top ten|publisher=University of Glasgow|access-date=23 March 2017}}</ref>  He serves as an adviser for many bodies, including the National Trust for Scotland and the Scottish National Gallery. In 2018, he published the first ever scholarly edition of Robert Burns and James Johnson's Scots Musical Museum in two volumes. He is currently working on a book, 'Smart City of Edinburgh: Routing the Enlightenment, 1660\u20131750' which uses innovation and current [[smart city]] theory on the geographical and social data from Edinburgh in 1660\u20131750.\n\n==Honors==\nPittock is also a fellow of the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]] (2004) and has been awarded or shortlisted for numerous prizes. He is one of few academics to have given a prize lecture at both the Royal Society of Edinburgh and the [[British Academy]], where he gave the Chatterton lecture in poetry in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chatterton Lectures on Poetry|url=http://www.britac.ac.uk/lectures/chatterton.cfm|publisher=Britac.ac.uk|accessdate=2 January 2014}}</ref> In 2011\u201313, he also convened the National Champions' Group, supporting the introduction and development of [[Scottish Studies]] in schools.<ref>{{cite web|last=Denholm|first=Andrew|title=Call for our politicians to unite on Scottish studies|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/education/call-for-our-politicians-to-unite-on-scottish-studies.17048256|work=The Herald|location=Glasgow|accessdate=2 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* ''The Scots Musical Museum\" (2 vols: 2018)\n*' 'Culloden'' (2016)\n* ''The Reception of Robert Burns in Europe'' (ed, 2014)\n* ''The Road to Independence ? Scotland in the Balance'' (2014)\n* ''Material Culture and Sedition'' (2013)\n* ''The Edinburgh Companion to Scottish Romanticism'' (ed, 2011) \n* ''Robert Burns in Global Culture'' (ed, 2011) \n* ''Loyalty and Identity'' (co-ed, 2010)\n* ''The Myth of the Jacobite Clans: The Jacobite Army in 1745'' (2009) \n* ''Scottish and Irish Romanticism'' (2008, corrected ed, 2011) \n* ''The Road to Independence? Scotland Since the Sixties'' (2008)\n* ''James Boswell'' (2007)\n* ''The Reception of Sir Walter Scott in Europe'' (ed, 2007; corrected ed, 2014)\n* ''The Edinburgh History of Scottish Literature'' (co-ed, 2006)\n* ''A New History of Scotland'' (2003)\n* ''James Hogg: The Jacobite Relics of Scotland'', 2 volumes, (2002\u201303)\n* ''Scottish Nationality'' (2001)\n* ''Celtic Identity and the British Image'' (1999)\n* ''Jacobitism'' (1998)\n* ''Inventing and Resisting Britain'' (1997)\n* ''The Myth of the Jacobite Clans'' (1995)\n* ''Poetry and Jacobite Politics in Eighteenth-Century Britain and Ireland'' (1994; paperback, 2006)\n* ''Spectrum of Decadence: The Literature of the 1890s'' (1993,reissued 2014, paperback 2016)\n* ''Clio's Clavers'' (1992)\n* ''The Invention of Scotland'' (1991, reissued 2014, paperback 2016)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.gla.ac.uk/schools/critical/research/researchcentresandnetworks/robertburnsstudies/edinburghenlightenment/ Centre for Robert Burns Studies]\n* [https://ora.ox.ac.uk/objects/uuid:6fa01d5c-e900-4ee8-9fb6-a8c3645e0bdd Full text of doctoral thesis, \"Decadence and the English tradition\"] via Oxford Research Archive\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pittock, Murray}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish historians]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n", "name_user": "Union1707", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated entry", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Murray_Pittock"}
{"title_page": "American Athletic Conference", "text_new": "{{short description|US college sports conference}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{use American English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox Athletic Conference\n| name = American Athletic Conference\n| short_name = The American\n| logo = American Athletic Conference logo.svg\n| logo_size = 175\n| established = {{Start date and age|1979|05|31}}<ref group=\"note\">The American is the legal all-sports successor to the [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)]]. The Big East was rebranded and reorganized as the American Athletic Conference on July 1, 2013.</ref>\n| association = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]\n| division = [[NCAA Division I|Division I]]\n| subdivision = [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|FBS]]\n| members = 11 (main) + 6 (associate)\n| sports = 22\n| mens = 10\n| womens = 12\n| region = * [[Southern United States|Southern]] {{small|(8 schools)}}\n** [[South Atlantic States|South Atlantic]]\n** [[East South Central States|East South Central]]\n** [[West South Central States|West South Central]]\n* [[Northeastern United States|Northeastern]] {{small|(3 schools)}}\n** [[Mid-Atlantic states|Mid-Atlantic]]\n* [[Midwestern United States|Midwestern]] {{small|(2 schools)}}\n** [[East North Central States|East North Central]]\n** [[West North Central States|West North Central]]\n| former_names = [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East]] {{small|(1979\u20132013)}}<ref group=\"note\">The American is the legal successor to the [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)]] and retains its charter. The current [[Big East Conference]] purchased the \"Big East\" name during the 2013 conference breakup.</ref>\n| hq_city = Providence\n| hq_state = Rhode Island\n| commissioner = [[Michael Aresco]] {{small|(since 2012)}}\n| website = {{url|www.theamerican.org}}\n| color = #041E41\n| font_color = #FFFFFF\n| map = American Athletic Conference map.svg\n| map_size = 275\n}}\nThe '''American Athletic Conference''' ('''The American''' or '''AAC'''), is an American [[List of NCAA conferences|collegiate athletic conference]], featuring 11 member universities and six associate member universities that compete in the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]'s (NCAA) [[NCAA Division I|Division I]], with its [[College football|football]] teams competing in the [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|Football Bowl Subdivision]] (FBS). Member universities represent a range of private and public universities of various enrollment sizes located primarily in [[Urban area|urban]] [[metropolitan area]]s in the [[Northeastern United States|Northeastern]], [[Midwestern United States|Midwestern]], and [[Southern United States|Southern]] regions of the [[United States]].<ref name=\"aac\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bigeast.org/News/tabid/435/Article/243706/new-name-in-college-sports-current-big-east-enters-new-era-as-american-athletic.aspx |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421031242/http://www.bigeast.org/News/tabid/435/Article/243706/new-name-in-college-sports-current-big-east-enters-new-era-as-american-athletic.aspx|archivedate=April 21, 2013|title=New Name in College Sports \u2013 Current BIG EAST Enters New Era as 'American Athletic Conference' |date=April 3, 2013|accessdate=April 3, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"oldbe\">{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/blog/_/name/katz_andy/id/9057093/the-steps-new-big-east-conference-college-basketball |title=What's next for the 'old Big East' |last=Katz |first=Andy |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=March 15, 2013 |accessdate=March 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe American's legal predecessor, the [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|original Big East Conference]], was considered one of the six collegiate [[Power Five conferences|power conferences]] of the [[Bowl Championship Series]] (BCS) era in college football, and The American inherited that status in the BCS's final season.<ref name=\"bcsname\">{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/9000502/catholic-7-schools-keep-big-east-name-new-league-next-season-according-sources |title=Catholic 7 to keep 'Big East' name for new league next season, according to sources |last=McMurphy |first=Brett |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=March 1, 2013 |accessdate=March 7, 2013}}</ref> With the advent of the [[College Football Playoff]] in 2014, The American became a [[Group of Five conferences|\"Group of Five\" conference]], which shares one automatic spot in the [[New Year's Six]] [[bowl game]]s.<ref group=\"note\">The other conferences in the \"Group of Five\" are [[Conference USA]] (C-USA), the [[Mid-American Conference]] (MAC), the [[Mountain West Conference]], and the [[Sun Belt Conference]].</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012/writers/stewart_mandel/11/12/college-football-playoff-six-bowls/index.html |title=Big East, rest of 'Group of Five' score win with six-bowl decision |last=Mandel |first=Stewart |magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=November 12, 2012 |accessdate=March 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe league is the product of [[2010\u201313 Big East Conference realignment|substantial turmoil]] in the [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|old Big East]] during the [[2010\u20132014 NCAA conference realignment|2010\u201314 conference realignment period]]. It is one of two conferences to emerge from the all-sports Big East in 2013. While the other successor, which does not sponsor football, purchased the [[Big East Conference]] name, The American inherited the old Big East's structure and is that conference's legal successor. However, both conferences claim 1979 as their founding date, and the same history up to 2013.<ref name=TheAmericanHistory>{{cite web|url=http://www.theamerican.org/sports/2013/6/22/ABOUT_0622134018.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209090628/http://www.theamerican.org/sports/2013/6/22/ABOUT_0622134018.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 9, 2014|title=The American Athletic Conference - About the American Athletic Conference|date=February 9, 2014|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name=BigEastHistory>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigeast.com/sports/2015/6/10/History.aspx|title=Big East Conference - BIG EAST Conference History|website=www.bigeast.com|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref> The American is headquartered in [[Providence, Rhode Island]], and led by Commissioner [[Michael Aresco]].<ref name=\"oldbe\"/><ref name=\"aresco\">{{cite news|url=http://www.delmarvanow.com/viewart/20130309/SPORTS/303090035/Big-East-completes-official-split-football-basketball |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130410175126/http://www.delmarvanow.com/viewart/20130309/SPORTS/303090035/Big-East-completes-official-split-football-basketball |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 10, 2013 |title=Big East completes official split of football, basketball |last=Russo |first=Ralph |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 8, 2013 |accessdate=March 17, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===The Big East===\n{{main|Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)}}\nThe Big East Conference was founded in 1979 as a basketball conference and included the colleges of [[Providence Friars|Providence]], [[St. John's Red Storm|St. John's]], [[Georgetown Hoyas|Georgetown]], and [[Syracuse Orange|Syracuse]], which in turn invited [[UConn Huskies|Connecticut]] (UConn), [[Holy Cross Crusaders|Holy Cross]], [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights|Rutgers]], and [[Boston College Eagles|Boston College]] to be members.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ajerseyguy.com/?p=5625 |title=Naming original Big East was simple |last=Blaudschun |first=Mark |publisher=AJerseyGuy.com |date=March 8, 2013 |accessdate=March 9, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408213431/http://ajerseyguy.com/?p=5625 |archivedate=April 8, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Crouthamel>{{cite web|url=http://www.suathletics.com/sports/2001/8/8/history.aspx|title=A Big East History and Retrospective, Part 1 |last=Crouthamel|first=Jake|date=December 8, 2000 |publisher=SUAthletics.com |accessdate=March 9, 2013}}</ref> UConn and Boston College would accept the invitation, while Holy Cross soon thereafter declined the invitation, and Rutgers eventually declined and remained in the [[Atlantic 10 Conference]] (then known as the Eastern 8 Conference). [[Seton Hall Pirates|Seton Hall]] was then invited as a replacement and the conference started play with seven members.<ref name=Crouthamel/>\n\n[[Villanova Wildcats|Villanova]] and [[Pittsburgh Panthers|Pittsburgh]] joined shortly thereafter under the leadership of the first Big East commissioner, [[Dave Gavitt]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/18/sports/ncaabasketball/dave-gavitt-the-big-easts-founder-dies-at-73.html|title=Dave Gavitt, the Big East's Founder, Dies at 73|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 17, 2011|accessdate=March 9, 2013|author=Sarah Maslin Nir}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Big East, Villanova Make It Official |agency=United Press International |newspaper=[[The Pittsburgh Press]] |date=March 13, 1980 |accessdate=March 9, 2013 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=xBshAAAAIBAJ&sjid=SFwEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4471,6402629&dq=big-east-conference+villanova }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pittsburgh To Join Big East |first= Richard F |last=Hanley |date=November 19, 1981 |accessdate=March 9, 2013 |newspaper=[[Record-Journal]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=schHAAAAIBAJ&sjid=u_8MAAAAIBAJ&pg=4292,2306993&dq=big-east-conference+football}}</ref>\n\nThe conference remained largely unchanged until 1991, when it began to sponsor football, adding [[Miami Hurricanes|Miami]] as a full member, and Rutgers, [[Temple Owls|Temple]], [[Virginia Tech Hokies|Virginia Tech]], and [[West Virginia Mountaineers|West Virginia]] as football-only members.<ref>{{cite web|title=Big East Football Timeline |newspaper=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]] |date=March 8, 2008 |url=http://articles.philly.com/2012-03-08/sports/31136038_1_big-east-football-football-only-member-football-schools |accessdate=March 9, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AEtk8rbY?url=http://articles.philly.com/2012-03-08/sports/31136038_1_big-east-football-football-only-member-football-schools |archivedate=August 27, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Rutgers and West Virginia were offered full all-sports membership in 1995, while Virginia Tech waited until 2000 for the same offer. Temple football was kicked out after the 2004 season, but rejoined in 2012 and intended to become a full member in 2013.\n\nThe unusual structure of the Big East, with the \"football\" and \"non-football\" schools, led to instability in the conference.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/08/sports/ncaabasketball/john-marinatto-resigns-as-big-east-commissioner.html|title=Commissioner John Marinatto Steps Down Amid Big East's Instability|last=Thamel|first=Pete|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 7, 2012|accessdate=March 9, 2013}}</ref> The waves of defection and replacement brought about by the conference realignments of [[2005 NCAA conference realignment|2005]] and [[2010\u20132014 NCAA conference realignment|the early 2010s]] revealed tension between the football-sponsoring and non-football schools that eventually led to the split of the conference in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/story/_/id/8801033/big-east-was-unwilling-meet-boise-state-terms-according-mike-aresco |title=Big East 'unwilling' to meet terms |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=January 3, 2013 |accessdate=March 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Realignment and reorganization===\n{{Location map+ | USA | width=450 | caption=[[File:Blue pog.svg|10px]] \u2013 All-sports member<br />[[File:Purple pog.svg|10px]] \u2013 Full, non-football member<br />[[File:Green pog.svg|10px]] \u2013 Associate member (football)<br />[[File:Yellow pog.svg|10px]] \u2013 Associate member (women's lacrosse)<br />[[File:Red pog.svg|10px]] \u2013 Associate member (women's rowing)| relief=yes | places=\n   {{Location map~ | USA | label=[[University of Central Florida|UCF]] | position=right | mark=Blue pog.svg | link=University of Central Florida | lat=28.6016 | long=-81.2005 }}\n   {{Location map~ | USA | label=[[University of Cincinnati|Cincinnati]] | position=top | mark=Blue pog.svg | link=University of Cincinnati | lat=39.132024 | long=-84.515548 }}\n   {{Location map~ | USA | label=[[East Carolina University|East Carolina]] | position=bottom | mark=Blue pog.svg | link=East Carolina University | lat=35.602 | long=-77.368 }}\n   {{Location map~ | USA | label=[[University of Florida|Florida]] | position=left | mark=Yellow pog.svg | link=University of Florida | lat=29.64833 | long=-82.34944 }}\n   {{Location map~ | USA | label=[[Old Dominion University|Old Dominion]] | position=right | mark=Red pog.svg | link=Old Dominion University | lat=36.88592 | long=-76.30453 }}\n   {{Location map~ | USA | label=[[University of Houston|Houston]] | position=left | mark=Blue pog.svg | link=University of Houston | lat=29.718922 | long=-95.339162 }}\n   {{Location map~ | USA | label=[[University of Memphis|Memphis]] | mark=Blue pog.svg | position=bottom| link=University of Memphis | lat=35.119 | long=-89.937 }}\n   {{Location map~ | USA | label=[[University of South Florida|South Florida]] | position=bottom | mark=Blue pog.svg | link=University of South Florida | lat=28.054561 | long=-82.413058 }}\n   {{Location map~ | USA  | label=[[Southern Methodist University|SMU]] | position=left | mark=Blue pog.svg | link=Southern Methodist University | lat=32.841 | long=-96.784 }}\n   {{Location map~ | USA | label=[[Tulane University|Tulane]] | position=bottom | mark=Blue pog.svg | link=Tulane University | lat=29.935344 | long=-90.122687 }}\n   {{Location map~ | USA | label=[[University of Tulsa|Tulsa]] | position=left | mark=Blue pog.svg | link=University of Tulsa | lat=36.152222 | long=-95.946389 }}\n   {{Location map~ | USA | label=[[California State University, Sacramento|Sacramento State]] | mark=Red pog.svg | link=California State University, Sacramento | lat=38.560222 | long=-121.424111\n}}\n   {{Location map~ | USA | label=[[San Diego State University|San Diego State]] | mark=Red pog.svg | link=San Diego State University | lat=32.775278 | long=-117.072222 }}\n   {{Location map~ | USA | label=[[Temple University|Temple]] | position=top | mark=Blue pog.svg | link=Temple University | lat=39.859751 | long=-75.229089 }}\n   {{Location map~ | USA | label=[[United States Naval Academy|Navy]] | position=right| mark=Green pog.svg | link=United States Naval Academy | lat=38.88 | long=-76.29 }}\n   {{Location map~ | USA | label=[[Vanderbilt University|Vanderbilt]] | position=top | mark=Yellow pog.svg | link=Vanderbilt University | lat=36.148649 | long=-86.804972 }}\n   {{Location map~ | USA | label=[[Wichita State University|Wichita State]] | position=top | mark=Purple pog.svg | link=Wichita State University | lat=37.688889 | long=-97.336111 }}\n}}\n\n{{Further|2010\u20132014 NCAA conference realignment|2010\u201313 Big East Conference realignment}}\nThe conference was reorganized following the tumultuous period of realignment that hobbled the Big East between 2010 and 2013. The Big East was one of the most severely impacted conferences during the most recent conference realignment period. In all, 14 member schools announced their departure for other conferences, and 15 other schools announced plans to join the conference (eight as all-sports members, and four for football only). Three of the latter group later backed out of their plans to join (one for all sports, and the other two for football only).\n\nOn December 15, 2012, the Big East's seven remaining non-FBS schools, all [[Catholic Church in the United States|Catholic]] institutions consisting of [[DePaul University|DePaul]], [[Georgetown University|Georgetown]], [[Marquette University|Marquette]], [[Providence College|Providence]], [[St. John's University (New York)|St. John's]], [[Seton Hall University|Seton Hall]], and [[Villanova University|Villanova]] announced that they voted unanimously to leave the Big East Conference effective June 30, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/story/_/id/8735330/big-east-direction-concerns-conference-catholic-schools-sources-say |title=Big East fate vexes Catholic schools |first1=Andy |last1=Katz |first2=Brett |last2=McMurphy |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=December 11, 2012 |accessdate=December 11, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/story/_/id/8749700/seven-schools-decide-leave-big-east-pursue-new-basketball-framework|title=Seven schools leaving Big East |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=December 15, 2012 | accessdate=December 15, 2012}}</ref> The \"Catholic 7\", by leaving, were looking for a more lucrative television deal than the one they would receive by remaining with the football schools.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/8817624/fleeing-big-east-schools-working-lucrative-tv-deal-basketball|title=Sources: 'Catholic 7' eyes big TV deal |last=Rovell |first=Darren |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=January 6, 2013 |accessdate=March 6, 2013}}</ref> In March 2013, representatives of the Catholic 7 announced they would leave the conference effective June 30, 2013, retaining the Big East name, $10 million, and the right to hold the [[Big East Men's Basketball Tournament|conference's basketball tournament]] at [[Madison Square Garden]].<ref name=\"bcsname\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://collegebasketballtalk.nbcsports.com/2013/03/05/catholic-7-has-framework-to-keep-big-east-name-msg-as-tourney-site/|title=Catholic 7 has framework to keep Big East name, MSG as tourney site|last=Harten|first=David|publisher=[[NBC Sports]] |date=March 5, 2013|accessdate=March 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the announcement of the departure of the Catholic 7 universities, the remaining ten football-playing members started the process of selecting a new name for the conference and choosing a new site to hold its basketball tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ajerseyguy.com/?p=5545 |title=Big East, Catholic 7 ready to make split official |last=Blaudschun |first=Mark |publisher=AJerseyGuy.com |date=March 6, 2013 |accessdate=March 7, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203102820/http://ajerseyguy.com/?p=5545 |archivedate=December 3, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/story/_/id/9019093/big-east-football-schools-keep-close-110-million-league-split-according-report |title=Report: $100M for football schools |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=March 5, 2013 |accessdate=March 7, 2013}}</ref> Various names were considered, with the \"America 12\" conference reportedly one of the finalists until rejected by college presidents sensitive of adding a number to the end of the conference name.<ref>[http://espn.go.com/college-sports/story/_/id/9130997/former-big-east-named-american-athletic-conference Former Big East to be named American Athletic Conference]. [[ESPN]]  (April 4, 2013). Retrieved on 2013-07-15.</ref> On April 3, 2013, the conference announced that it had chosen a new name: American Athletic Conference.<ref name=\"aac\"/> The conference also revealed that it prefers the nickname \"The American\" because it was thought \"AAC\" would cause too much confusion with the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] (ACC).<ref name=logo>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/college/2013/05/29/american-athletic-conference-new-logo/2369991|title=American Athletic Conference unveils its primary logos|last=Wolken|first=Dan|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=May 29, 2013 |quote=Beyond the challenge of avoiding something that looked corporate, the league also couldn't build the logo around an acronym. From the very beginning, the conference office has been adamant that it wants to be known as The American instead of the AAC to avoid confusion with the Atlantic Coast Conference.}}</ref> \n\nTo restate and clarify a somewhat confusing series of events: on July 1, the original Big East changed its name to the American Athletic Conference, while the \"Catholic 7\" split off and joined Butler, Creighton, and Xavier to form a \"new\" Big East. While The American is reckoned as the original conference and the \"new\" Big East is considered a spinoff, the \"new\" Big East retained the rights to the original Big East logo, trademarks, and men's basketball tournament.\n\nLouisville and Rutgers spent one season in the newly renamed conference. On July 1, 2014, Louisville joined the ACC<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theacc.com/genrel/112812aaa.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=November 28, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121212230217/http://www.theacc.com/genrel/112812aaa.html |archivedate=December 12, 2012 }}</ref> and Rutgers joined the [[Big Ten Conference]].<ref>[http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/college/rutgers-accepts-invitation-join-big-ten-article-1.1204813 Rutgers Scarlet Knights accept invitation to join Big Ten as Board of Governors gives go-ahead to athletic director Tim Pernetti]. ''[[Daily News (New York)|NY Daily News]]'' (November 19, 2012). Retrieved on 2013-07-15.</ref> On that same day, [[East Carolina University|East Carolina]], [[Tulane University|Tulane]], and [[University of Tulsa|Tulsa]] joined The American for all sports, while [[California State University, Sacramento|Sacramento State]] and [[San Diego State University|San Diego State]] joined as associate members for women's rowing.<ref name=\"glance\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2014/06/29/at-a-glance-latest-wave-of-conference-realignment/11720925/ |title=At a glance: Latest wave of conference realignment |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=June 29, 2014 |accessdate=June 30, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://theamerican.org/news/2014/3/25/ROWING_0325144625.aspx|title=The American adds Associate Members for Women's Rowing|publisher=American Athletic Conference|date=March 25, 2014|accessdate=May 17, 2014}}</ref> Navy joined as an associate member in football on July 1, 2015.<ref name=\"glance\"/>\n\nFor the next several years, The American did not discuss the addition of any new members. However, in March 2017, media reports indicated that the conference was seriously considering adding one or more new members specifically as basketball upgrades. [[Wichita State University|Wichita State]], [[University of Dayton|Dayton]], and [[Virginia Commonwealth University|VCU]] were reportedly considered, with Wichita State being seen as the strongest candidate.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/wichita-state-getting-serious-evaluation-to-join-american-athletic-conference/ |title=Wichita State getting 'serious evaluation' to join American Athletic Conference |first=Dennis |last=Dodd |work=CBSSports.com |date=March 3, 2017 |accessdate=March 6, 2017}}</ref> By the end of that month, it was reported that talks between the American and Wichita State had advanced to the point that the two sides were discussing a timeline for membership, with the possibility of the [[Wichita State Shockers|Shockers]] joining as a full but non-football member as early as the 2017\u201318 school year. The report indicated that a final decision would be made in April.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.si.com/college-basketball/2017/03/30/wichita-state-gregg-marshall-aac-american-athletic-conference-missouri-valley |title=Sources: Wichita State in talks to join AAC as soon as 2017\u201318 |first=Pete |last=Thamel |magazine=Sports Illustrated |date=March 31, 2017 |accessdate=March 31, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/story/_/id/19042825/wichita-state-shockers-eyes-2017-move-american-athletic-conference|title=Source: Wichita St. eyes 2017 move to AAC|work=ESPN.com|access-date=April 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fanragsports.com/news/aac-preparing-wichita-state-join-league-2017-18/|title=AAC Is Preparing For Wichita State To Join League In 2017\u201318|website=www.fanragsports.com|language=English|access-date=April 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170405170056/https://www.fanragsports.com/news/aac-preparing-wichita-state-join-league-2017-18/|archive-date=April 5, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The conference's board of directors voted unanimously on April 7 to add Wichita State effective in July 2017, making the Shockers the league's first full non-football member since the Big East split.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://theamerican.org/news/2017/4/7/GEN_0407172824.aspx |title=Wichita State to Become Member of American Athletic Conference |publisher=American Athletic Conference |date=April 7, 2017 |accessdate=April 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Departure of Connecticut====\nOn June 21, 2019, a Boston-area sports news website, ''Digital Sports Desk'', revealed that UConn was expected to announce by the end of the month that it would leave the American for the [[Big East|Big East Conference]] in 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalsportsdesk.com/ncaa-basketball/big-east/uconn-to-return-to-big-east/ |title=UConn to Return to Big East |publisher=Digital Sports Desk |date=June 21, 2019 |accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref> The story was picked up by multiple national media outlets the next day. The main issue that reportedly had to be resolved prior to any official announcement was the future of UConn football, as the Big East does not sponsor that sport, and sources indicated that the American had no interest in retaining UConn as a football-only member. Reportedly, American Conference insiders were not surprised by UConn's prospective move, as that school had been vigorously opposed to that league's most recently announced television deal.<ref name=\"Borzello, Schlabach\">{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/college-sports/story/_/id/27030819/sources-uconn-expected-rejoin-big-east |title=Sources: UConn expected to rejoin Big East |first1=Jeff |last1=Borzello |first2=Mark |last2=Schlabach |website=ESPN.com |date=June 22, 2019 |accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Thamel 2019-06-22\">{{cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/sources-u-conn-move-to-the-big-east-inevitable-151200471.html |title=Sources: UConn move to the Big East inevitable |first=Pete |last=Thamel |work=Yahoo Sports |date=June 22, 2019 |accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nNational media believed that should UConn leave the American, the conference's likeliest response would be to bring in two new schools\u2014one for football only and a second in non-football sports, similar to the American's sequential additions of Navy and Wichita State. The most likely prospects for football-only membership were seen as [[Army Black Knights football|Army]] (currently an FBS independent, with most of its other sports in the [[Patriot League]]), and [[Air Force Falcons football|Air Force]] (currently an all-sports member of the [[Mountain West Conference]]). Any of several schools could potentially fill the non-football slot, with Pete Thamel of [[Yahoo Sports]] considering [[VCU Rams|VCU]] to be \"the most logical target there.\" Thamel dismissed the prospect of the American adding a new all-sports member, saying \"there's no obvious candidate who could add value in both basketball and football.\"<ref name=\"Borzello, Schlabach\"/><ref name=\"Thamel 2019-06-22\"/>\n\nOn June 24, 2019, it was reported that the Big East had formally approved an invitation for UConn to join the conference.<ref>{{cite web |title=Big East presidents approve UConn's invitation to join conference; football program's future remains uncertain |url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/big-east-presidents-approve-uconns-invitation-to-join-conference-football-programs-future-remains-uncertain/ |website=CBSSports.com |accessdate=25 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref> On June 26, 2019, the UConn Board of Trustees accepted the invitation and they are expected to join the league for the 2020-2021 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collegebasketball.nbcsports.com/2019/06/26/its-official-uconn-is-back-in-the-big-east/|title=It's official: UConn is back in the Big East|last=Dauster|first=Rob|date=2019-06-26|website=CollegeBasketballTalk|language=en|access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref> On July 26, media reports indicated that UConn and The American had reached a buyout agreement that confirmed UConn's Big East arrival date as July 1, 2020, paying the American a $17 million exit fee.<ref name=\"UConn buyout\">{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/college-sports/story/_/id/27263372/uconn-leaving-aac-20-owe-17m-exit-fee |title=UConn leaving AAC in '20, will owe $17M exit fee |first=Jeff |last=Borzello |website=ESPN.com |date=July 26, 2019 |accessdate=July 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt was widely reported that UConn was \"rejoining\" the Big East, given that the Huskies would be reunited with many of the schools against which it played for three decades in the original Big East. Indeed, UConn was the last charter member of the old Big East still playing in The American.\n\n===Commissioners===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:175px;\"| Name\n! style=\"width:150px;\"| Term\n|-\n| [[Michael Aresco]]\n| 2013\u2013present<ref name=\"aresco\"/>\n|}\n\n===Membership timeline===\n{{Details|topic=members of the old Big East|Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)#Membership timeline}}\n\n<!-- NOTE: \"UCF\" not \"Central Florida\"; this article uses WP's standard naming convention. -->\n<!-- NOTE: This lists only current or future members of The American, not the old Big East. -->\n<timeline>\nImageSize = width:1000 height:auto barincrement:20\nPeriod = from:2013 till:2021\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal\nPlotArea = right:20 left:0 bottom:50 top:5 #> to display a count on left side of graph, use \"left:20\" to suppr