lane Green Wave}}\n|-\n!{{sort|Tulsa|[[University of Tulsa]]}}\n|[[Tulsa, Oklahoma]]\n|1894\n|2014\n|Private\n|3,343<ref>{{cite web|url=https://utulsa.edu/about/tu-fast-facts/|title=TU Fast Facts - The University of Tulsa|publisher=|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|[[Tulsa Golden Hurricane|Golden Hurricane]]\n|{{college color boxes|Tulsa Golden Hurricane}}\n|-\n!{{sort|Wichita State|[[Wichita State University]]}}<ref group=\"note\">Non-football member.</ref>\n|[[Wichita, Kansas]]\n|1895\n|2017\n|Public\n|15,778<ref>http://webs.wichita.edu/depttools/depttoolsmemberfiles/opa/BIPM/Enrollment_Fall_Census_OPAweb.pdf</ref>\n|[[Wichita State Shockers|Shockers]]\n|{{college color boxes|Wichita State Shockers}}\n|}\n\n===Associate members===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Institution\n!Location\n!Founded\n!Joined\n!Enrollment\n!Nickname\n!class=\n!Sport\n!Primary<br />Conference\n|-\n! {{sort|Florida|[[University of Florida]]}}\n| [[Gainesville, Florida]]\n| 1853\n| 2018\n| 51,474\n| [[Florida Gators women's lacrosse|Gators]]\n| {{college color boxes|Florida Gators}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Women's lacrosse\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]]\n|-\n! [[Vanderbilt University]]\n| [[Nashville, Tennessee]]\n| 1873\n| 2018\n| 12,686\n| [[Vanderbilt Commodores|Commodores]]\n| {{college color boxes|Vanderbilt Commodores}}\n|-\n!{{sort|Navy|[[United States Naval Academy]]}} (Navy)\n|[[Annapolis, Maryland]]\n|1845\n|2015\n|4,400\n|[[Navy Midshipmen|Midshipmen]]\n|{{college color boxes|Navy Midshipmen}}\n|Football\n|[[Patriot League]]\n|-\n! [[Old Dominion University]]\n| [[Norfolk, Virginia]]\n| 1930\n| 2018\n| 24,375\n| [[Old Dominion Monarchs|Monarchs]]\n| {{college color boxes|Old Dominion Monarchs}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Women's rowing\n| [[Conference USA|C-USA]]\n|-\n! {{sort|Sacramento|[[California State University, Sacramento]]}} {{small|(Sacramento State)}}\n|[[Sacramento, California]]\n|1947\n|2015\n|28,811\n|[[Sacramento State Hornets|Hornets]]\n|{{college color boxes|Sacramento State Hornets}}\n|[[Big Sky Conference|Big Sky]]\n|-\n![[San Diego State University]]\n|[[San Diego|San Diego, California]]\n|1897\n|2015\n|29,392\n|[[San Diego State Aztecs|Aztecs]]\n|{{college color boxes|San Diego State Aztecs}}\n|[[Mountain West Conference|Mountain West]]\n|}\n\n<!-- ====Future associate members====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%; width:97%;\"\n|-\n!Institution\n!Location\n!Founded\n!Joining\n!Enrollment\n!Nickname\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Colors\n!Sport\n!Primary<br />Conference\n|}\n-->\n\n===Former full members===\nThree full members have departed from the conference.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Institution\n!Location\n!Founded\n!Joined\n!Left\n!Nickname\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Colors\n!Current<br>conference\n|-\n![[Rutgers University\u2013New Brunswick|Rutgers University]]\n|[[New Brunswick, New Jersey]]\n|1766\n|1991<ref group=\"note\">Rutgers joined the conference in 1991 as a football-only member, and joined in all-sports in 1995.</ref>\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 2014\n|[[Rutgers Scarlet Knights|Scarlet Knights]]\n|{{college color boxes|Rutgers Scarlet Knights|order=1}}\n|[[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]]\n|-\n!{{sort|Louisville|[[University of Louisville]]}}\n|[[Louisville, Kentucky]]\n|1798\n|2005\n|[[Louisville Cardinals|Cardinals]]\n|{{college color boxes|Louisville Cardinals}}\n|[[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]]\n|-\n!{{sort|Louisville|[[University of Connecticut]]}}\n|[[Storrs, Connecticut]]\n|1881\n|1979\n|2020\n|[[UConn Huskies|Huskies]]\n|{{college color boxes|UConn Huskies}}\n|[[Big East Conference|Big East]]\n|}\n\n===Former associate members===\nOne associate member has left the conference.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Institution\n!Location\n!Founded\n!Joined\n!Left\n!Nickname\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Colors\n!Sport\n!Primary<br>conference\n!Conference in<br>Former AAC Sport\n|-\n![[Villanova University]]\n|[[Villanova, Pennsylvania]]\n|1842\n|2013\n|2015\n|[[Villanova Wildcats|Wildcats]]\n|{{college color boxes|Villanova Wildcats}}\n|Rowing\n|[[Big East Conference|Big East]]\n|[[Colonial Athletic Association|CAA]]\n|}\n\n==Sports==\nThe American currently sponsors championship competition in 10 men's and 12 women's NCAA sanctioned sports. [[Old Dominion University|Old Dominion]], [[California State University, Sacramento|Sacramento State]] and [[San Diego State University|San Diego State]] are associate members for women's rowing.<ref>[http://www.theamerican.org/sports/2013/6/22/ABOUT_0622133126.aspx?path=about The Official Site of The American Athletic Conference \u2013 Sponsored Sports]. American Athletic Conference. Retrieved on June 10, 2014.</ref> The newest conference sport of women's lacrosse, added for the 2018\u201319 school year, has six participating schools, with four full American members plus [[University of Florida|Florida]] and [[Vanderbilt University|Vanderbilt]] as single-sport associates.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://theamerican.org/news/2017/10/11/GEN_1011175626.aspx |title=American Athletic Conference to Sponsor Women's Lacrosse Beginning in 2019 |publisher=American Athletic Conference |date=October 11, 2017 |accessdate=October 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nUnder NCAA rules reflecting the large number of male scholarship participants in football and attempting to address [[gender equity]] concerns (see also [[Title IX]]), each member institution is required to provide more women's varsity sports than men's.<ref group=\"note\">Under NCAA Bylaw 20.9.4, all Division I schools are required to sponsor a minimum of seven men's and seven women's sports, or six men's and eight women's sports. Bylaw 20.9.7.1 imposes the latter requirement on FBS schools. FCS schools, under Bylaw 20.9.8.1, may use either requirement. Note that this does not explicitly require that a school sponsor two more women's sports than men's sports. See {{cite web|url=http://ncaapublications.com/productdownloads/D113.pdf |title=2012\u201313 NCAA Division I Manual |publisher=[[NCAA]] |accessdate=March 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Sport || width=60 | Men's ||Women's\n|-\n|[[Baseball]]||{{center|8}}||{{center|\u2013}}\n|-\n|[[Basketball]]||{{center|11}}||{{center|11}}\n|-\n|[[Cross country running|Cross Country]]||{{center|9}}||{{center|11}}\n|-\n|[[College football|Football]]||{{center|11}}||{{center|\u2013}}\n|-\n|[[Golf]]||{{center|10}}||{{center|10}}\n|-\n| [[College lacrosse|Lacrosse]] || {{center|\u2013}} || {{center|5}}\n|-\n|[[College rowing (United States)|Rowing]]||{{center|\u2013}}||{{center|7}}\n|-\n|[[College soccer|Soccer]]||{{center|7}}||{{center|9}}\n|-\n|[[Softball]]||{{center|\u2013}}||{{center|7}}\n|-\n|[[Swimming (sport)|Swimming]] & [[Diving (sport)|Diving]]||{{center|3}}||{{center|5}}\n|-\n||[[Tennis]]||{{center|9}}||{{center|11}}\n|-\n||[[Track and field#Indoor|Track and Field (Indoor)]]||{{center|8}}||{{center|11}}\n|-\n||[[Track and field#Outdoor|Track and Field (Outdoor)]]||{{center|8}}||{{center|11}}\n|-\n|[[Volleyball]]||{{center|\u2013}}||{{center|11}}\n|}\n\n{{notelist|group=s}}\n\n===Men's sponsored sports by school===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%; width:90%;\"\n|-\n! School !! Baseball !! Basketball !! Cross<br />Country !! Football !! Golf !! Soccer !! Swimming<br />& Diving !! Tennis !! Track & Field<br />(Indoor) !! Track & Field<br />(Outdoor)!! Total\n|-\n| Cincinnati || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{N}} || {{Y}} || {{N}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || 9\n|-\n| East Carolina || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{N}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || 9\n|-\n| Houston || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{N}} || {{N}} || {{N}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || 7\n|-\n| Memphis || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{N}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || {{Y}} || 9\n|-\n| South Florida || {{Y}}