}} || {{N}} || {{N}} || {{N}} || {{N}} || {{N}} || {{N}} || 1\n|-\n| Vanderbilt || {{N}} || {{N}} || {{N}} || {{Y}} || {{N}} || {{N}} || {{N}} || {{N}} || {{N}} || {{N}} || {{N}} || {{N}} || 1\n|-\n|'''Totals''' || 11 || 11 || 10 || 5 || 7 || 9 || 7 || 5 || 11 || 11 || 11 || 11 || 109\n|}\n\n'''Women's varsity sports not sponsored by The American which are played by conference schools:'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:90%;\"\n|-\n! School !! Beach<br>Volleyball !! Bowling !! Fencing !! Field Hockey !! Equestrian !! Gymnastics !! Rifle<ref group=\"note\" name=\"rifle\"/> !! Sailing\n|-\n| Memphis || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 ||\u2014 || [[Great America Rifle Conference|GARC]] || \u2014\n|-\n| South Florida || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014  || \u2014 || [[South Atlantic Intercollegiate Sailing Association|SAISA]]\n|-\n| SMU || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || Independent || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| Temple || \u2014 || \u2014|| [[National Intercollegiate Women's Fencing Association|NIWFA]] || [[Big East Conference|Big East]] || \u2014 || Independent  || \u2014|| \u2014\n|-\n| Tulane || Independent || [[Southland Bowling League|Southland]] || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014|| \u2014  ||\u2014 || \u2014\n|}\n* '''Women's Bowling''' \u2013 The [[Southland Conference]] provides administrative support for the [[Southland Bowling League]], but the SBL operates independently from regular conference operations.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Southland Bowling League Established|url=http://southland.org/news/2015/1/20/GEN_0120152535.aspx?path=general|publisher=Southland Conference|accessdate=January 24, 2014|date=January 20, 2014}}</ref> The women's bowling league was established in 2015 and includes Southland Conference members [[Sam Houston State Bearkats|Sam Houston State]] and [[Stephen F. Austin Lumberjacks and Ladyjacks|Stephen F. Austin]], plus [[Arkansas State Red Wolves|Arkansas State]], [[Louisiana Tech Bulldogs and Lady Techsters|Louisiana Tech]], [[Tulane Green Wave|Tulane]], [[Valparaiso Crusaders|Valparaiso]], [[Vanderbilt Commodores|Vanderbilt]], and [[Youngstown State Penguins|Youngstown State]].\n\n==NCAA team championships==\n<ref>http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/champs_records_book/Overall.pdf</ref>\n\nExcluded from this list are all national championships earned [[List of college athletics championship game outcomes|outside the scope of NCAA competition]], including [[College football national championships in NCAA Division I FBS|Division I FBS football titles]], women's [[Association for Intercollegiate Athletics for Women championships|AIAW championships]], [[National Collegiate Equestrian Association|equestrian titles]], and retroactive [[Helms Athletic Foundation|Helms Athletic Foundation titles]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!width=180| School\n!width=45| Total\n!width=45| Men\n!width=45| Women\n!width=45| Co-ed\n!width=100| Nickname\n!width=300| Most successful sport (Titles)\n|-\n|[[University of Houston]]\n|[[Houston Cougars#NCAA team championships|17]]\n|17\n|0\n|0\n|[[Houston Cougars|Cougars]]\n| [[NCAA Division I Men's Golf Championships#Team titles|Men's golf (16)]]\n|-\n|[[Southern Methodist University]]\n|[[SMU Mustangs#NCAA team championships|4]]\n|4\n|0\n|0\n|[[SMU Mustangs|Mustangs]]\n| [[NCAA Men's Division I Outdoor Track and Field Championships#Team titles|Men's outdoor track & field (2)]]\n|-\n|[[Temple University]]\n|[[Temple Owls#NCAA team championships|3]]\n|1\n|2\n|0\n|[[Temple Owls|Owls]]\n| [[NCAA Division I Women's Lacrosse Championship#Team titles|Women's lacrosse (2)]]\n|-\n|[[University of Cincinnati]]\n|[[Cincinnati Bearcats#NCAA team championships|2]]\n|2\n|0\n|0\n|[[Cincinnati Bearcats|Bearcats]]\n| [[NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament#Titles by school|Men's basketball (2)]]\n|-\n|-\n|[[Tulane University]]\n|[[Tulane Green Wave#NCAA team championships|1]]\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|[[Tulane Green Wave|Green Wave]]\n| [[NCAA Men's Tennis Championship#Team titles|Men's tennis (1)]]\n|-\n|[[University of Tulsa]]\n|[[Tulsa Golden Hurricane#NCAA team championships|1]]\n|0\n|1\n|0\n|[[Tulsa Golden Hurricane|Golden Hurricane]]\n| [[NCAA Division I Women's Golf Championships#Team titles|Women's golf (1)]]\n|-\n|[[Wichita State University]]\n|[[Wichita State Shockers#NCAA team championships|1]]\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|[[Wichita State Shockers|Shockers]]\n| [[College World Series|Baseball (1)]]\n|-\n|[[University of Central Florida]]\n|[[UCF Knights#NCAA team championships|1]]\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|[[UCF Knights|Knights]]\n|[[College football national championships in NCAA Division I FBS|Football (1)]]\n|-\n|[[University of Memphis]]\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|[[Memphis Tigers|Tigers]]\n|n/a\n|-\n|[[University of South Florida]]\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|[[South Florida Bulls|Bulls]]\n|n/a\n|-\n|[[East Carolina University]]\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|[[East Carolina Pirates|Pirates]]\n|n/a\n|}\nSee also:\n[[List of NCAA schools with the most NCAA Division I championships]],\n[[List of NCAA schools with the most Division I national championships]], and\n[[NCAA Division I#Conferences|NCAA Division I FBS Conferences]]\n\n==Football==\n{{see also|Bowl Championship Series|College Football Playoff}}\nThe conference began football during the 1991\u201392 season, and was a founding member of the [[Bowl Championship Series]].<ref>{{cite web| title=BCS Chronology | url=http://www.bcsfootball.org/bcsfb/history | work=bcsfootball.org | publisher=[[Fox Sports (USA)|Fox Sports]] | accessdate=November 12, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080418091328/http://www.bcsfootball.org/bcsfb/history |archivedate = April 18, 2008}}</ref> Previously conference opponents operated on a two-year cycle, as a home-and-home series.<ref>{{cite news|last=Myerberg|first=Paul|title=Big East announces divisions, adds conference title game|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2012/11/13/big-east-divisions-championship-game/1702851/|newspaper=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=December 10, 2012 |date=November 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; float:right;\" auto;\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#d81e05\"| <span style=\"color:white;\">West Division</span> !! style=\"background:#002654\"| <span style=\"color:white;\">East Division</span>\n|-\n| [[Houston Cougars football|Houston]] || [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati]]\n|-\n|[[Memphis Tigers football|Memphis]] || [[East Carolina Pirates football|East Carolina]]\n|-   \n|[[Navy Midshipmen football|Navy]] || [[South Florida Bulls football|South Florida]]\n|-\n| [[SMU Mustangs football|SMU]] || [[Temple Owls football|Temple]]      \n|-\n| [[Tulane Green Wave football|Tulane]] || [[UCF Knights football|UCF]]\n|-\n| [[Tulsa Golden Hurricane football|Tulsa]] ||\n|}\n\nThe conference previously did not have enough teams to form divisions, but now does after [[United States Naval Academy|Navy]] joined the conference in 2015.<ref group=\"note\">At the time Navy joined in football, the NCAA required 12 teams for a conference to conduct divisional play and stage a championship game that was exempt from the NCAA-imposed limit of 12 regular-season games. Starting with the 2016 season, a conference can conduct an \"exempt\" championship game with fewer than 12 members, as long as it either plays in two divisions or conducts a full round-robin schedule.</ref> When Navy joined in 2015 and divisions were created, Navy was placed in the West division along with Houston, Memphis, SMU, Tulane, and Tulsa. Teams play eight conference games a season. Since 2015, each team has played the other five teams in its own division, as well as three teams from the other division, operating in a four-year cycle ensuring that each school will play every conference opponent at home and on the road at least once in the four-year cycle.<ref>{{cite news|title=American Announces Football Schedule Format for 2015\u201318|url=http://theamerican.org/news/2014/12/18/FB_1218143422.aspx|newspaper=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=December 18, 2014|date=December 18, 2012}}</ref> The East and West division winners, determined by final conference record, meet in the [[American Athletic Conference Football Championship Game]], which is played at the home site of one of the division winners. \n\nWith the departure of UConn after the 2019 season, divisions were affected by the reduction to an uneven number of teams. The American has no immediate plan to add another team to rebalance division, so divisions have been eliminated from the conference for the time being. The championship game will now be played by the two teams that achieved the best record in regular season conference play.\n\nLike the conference itself, football experienced much transition through its history \u2013 in fact it was the main force behind such departures and expansion. In 2003, the BCS announced that it would adjust the automatic bids granted to its six founding conferences based on results from 2004 to 2007. With the addition of [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati]], [[Louisville Cardinals|Louisville]], and [[South Florida Bulls|South Florida]] in 2005, the conference retained its BCS automatic-qualifying status. In 2007, South Florida rose to No. 2 in the BCS rankings, but finished No. 21 in the final poll. Cincinnati finished the 2009 regular season undefeated at 12\u20130, and ranked No. 3 in the final BCS standings, barely missing the opportunity to play for the BCS National Championship. The conference was 9\u20137 (.563) in [[BCS Bowl#Bowl games|BCS bowl games]], the third highest winning percentage amongst the AQ conferences. After the 2017 Season, the University of Central Florida Knights, a member of the American, went undefeated but was not invited to the College Football Playoff. They earned the Group of Five's New Years Six bowl bid and defeated Auburn in the Peach Bowl. They would claim a national championship, which was recognized by the Colley Matrix, one of the NCAA recognized selectors of the national champion in football.\n\n===All-time school and conference records===\nAs of the conclusion of the [[2019 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2019 season]].\nConference wins and losses are since the formation of The American.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center; margin:1em auto; width:90%;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n! colspan=\"4\"|Overall\n! colspan=\"3\"|Conference\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Bowl <br> Appearances\n! rowspan=\"2\"|The American <br> Championships\n! rowspan=\"2\"|National <br> Championships\n|-\n! W !! L !! T !! Win %\n! W !! L !! Win %\n|-\n| [[South Florida Bulls football|South Florida]]\n|157\n|119\n|0||{{winpct|157|119}}\n|29\n|27|| {{winpct|29|27}} || 10 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[Navy Midshipmen football|Navy]]\n|720\n|570\n|57|| {{winpct|720|570|57}}\n|27\n|13|| {{winpct|27|13}} || 24 || 0 || 1\n|-\n| [[Tulsa Golden Hurricane football|Tulsa]]\n|623\n|506\n|27|| {{winpct|623|506|27}}\n|16\n|32|| {{winpct|16|32}} || 21 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[UCF Knights football|UCF]]\n|259\n|212\n|1|| {{winpct|259|212|1}}\n|41\n|15|| {{winpct|41|15}} || 10 || 4 || 1\n|-\n| [[Houston Cougars football|Houston]]\n|445\n|374\n|15||{{winpct|445|374|15}}\n|34\n|22||{{winpct|34|22}} || 27 || 1 || 0\n|-\n| [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati]]\n|621\n|589\n|50||{{winpct|621|589|50}}\n|33\n|24||{{winpct|33|24}} || 19 || 1 || 0\n|-\n| [[East Carolina Pirates football|East Carolina]]\n|444\n|428\n|12|| {{winpct|444|428|12}}\n|13\n|35|| {{winpct|13|35}} || 20 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[Memphis Tigers football|Memphis]]\n|502\n|518\n|33|| {{winpct|502|518|33}}\n|38\n|21||{{winpct|38|21}} || 13 || 1 || 0\n|-\n| [[SMU Mustangs football|SMU]]\n|504\n|550\n|54|| {{winpct|504|550|54}}\n|23\n|33||{{winpct|23|33}} || 17 || 0 || 3\n|-\n| [[Tulane Green Wave football|Tulane]]\n|531\n|648\n|38|| {{winpct|531|648|38}}\n|15\n|33||{{winpct|15|33}} || 13 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[Temple Owls football|Temple]]\n|474\n|586\n|52|| {{winpct|474|586|52}}\n|35\n|21|| {{winpct|35|21}}|| 8 || 1 || 0\n|}\n\n===Conference champions===\n{{main|American Athletic Conference Football Championship Game}}\n{{Details|topic=football champions of the Big East Conference from 1991 to 2012|Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)#Champions}}\nThe American Championship Game pits the Eastern Division representative against the Western Division representative in a game held following the conclusion of the regular season. The site of the Championship Game is the home stadium of the division champion with the best overall conference record. In the event that the two division champions are tied, then the head-to-head record shall be used as the tiebreaker. Prior to the 2015 season, when the conference split into two six-team divisions and created a conference championship game, The American awarded its championship to the team(s) with the best overall conference record.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"  style=\"text-align:center; margin:1em auto; font-size:95%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | || colspan=2 | Record || colspan=2 | Ranking || ||\n|-\n! Year || Champions || style=\"width:12%;\" | Conference || style=\"width:12%;\" | Overall || style=\"width:10%;\" | AP || style=\"width:10%;\" | Coaches || Bowl result || Head coach\n|-\n| {{sort|2013|[[2013 American Athletic Conference football season|2013]]}} || {{sort|Central Florida|[[2013 UCF Knights football team|UCF]]}} || 8\u20130 || 12\u20131 || #10 || #12 || '''W''' [[2014 Fiesta Bowl (January)|Fiesta Bowl]] 52\u201342 vs. [[2013 Baylor Bears football team|Baylor]]{{sup|\u2020}} || [[George O'Leary]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{sort|2014|[[2014 American Athletic Conference football season|2014]]}}\n| {{sort|Central Florida|[[2014 UCF Knights football team|UCF]]}} || 7\u20131 || 9\u20134 || N/A || N/A || '''L''' [[2014 St. Petersburg Bowl|St. Petersburg Bowl]] 27\u201334 vs. [[2014 NC State Wolfpack football team|NC State]] || [[George O'Leary]]\n|-\n| {{sort|Cincinnati|[[2014 Cincinnati Bearcats football team|Cincinnati]]}} || 7\u20131 || 9\u20134 || N/A || N/A || '''L''' [[2014 Military Bowl|Military Bowl]] 17\u201333 vs. [[2014 Virginia Tech Hokies football team|Virginia Tech]] || [[Tommy Tuberville]]\n|-\n| {{sort|Memphis|[[2014 Memphis Tigers football team|Memphis]]}} || 7\u20131 || 10\u20133 || #25 || #25 || '''W''' [[2014 Miami Beach Bowl|Miami Beach Bowl]] 55\u201348 vs. [[2014 BYU Cougars football team|BYU]] || [[Justin Fuente]]\n|-\n| {{sort|2015|[[2015 American Athletic Conference football season|2015]]}}  || {{sort|Houston|[[2015 Houston Cougars football team|Houston]]}} || 7\u20131 || 13\u20131 || #8 || #8 || '''W'''  [[2015 Peach Bowl|Peach Bowl]] 38\u201324  vs. [[2015 Florida State Seminoles football team|Florida State]]{{sup|\u2020}}  || [[Tom Herman (American football)|Tom Herman]]\n|-\n|[[2016 American Athletic Conference Football Championship Game|2016]]\n|[[2016 Temple Owls football team|Temple]]\n|7\u20131\n|10\u20133\n|#23\n|#24\n|'''L''' [[2016 Military Bowl|Military Bowl]] 26\u201334 vs. [[2016 Wake Forest Demon Deacons football team|Wake Forest]]\n|[[Matt Rhule]]\n|-\n| [[2017 American Athletic Conference Football Championship Game|2017]]\n| [[2017 UCF Knights football team|UCF]]\n| 8\u20130\n| 13\u20130\n| #6\n| #7\n| '''W''' [[2018 Peach Bowl (January)|Peach Bowl]] 34\u201327 vs. [[2017 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]]{{sup|\u2020}}\n| [[Scott Frost]]\n|-\n| [[2018 American Athletic Conference Football Championship Game|2018]]\n| [[2018 UCF Knights football team|UCF]]\n| 8\u20130\n| 12\u20131\n| #11\n| #12\n| '''L''' [[2019 Fiesta Bowl (January)|Fiesta Bowl]] 40\u201332 vs. [[2018 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]]{{sup|\u2020}}\n| [[Josh Heupel]]\n|-\n| [[2019 American Athletic Conference Football Championship Game|2019]]\n| [[2019 Memphis Tigers football team|Memphis]]\n| 7\u20131\n| 12\u20132\n| #17\n| #17\n| '''L''' [[2019 Cotton Bowl Classic|Cotton Bowl]] 39\u201353 vs. [[2019 Penn State Nittany Lions football team|Penn State]]{{sup|\u2020}}\n| [[Mike Norvell]]\n|}\n* {{sup|\u2020}} [[Bowl Championship Series|BCS]] or [[New Year's Six|NY6]] Bowl Game\n<!-- ====Conference Championship Game====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\" width=80%\n|-\n!Season\n!colspan=\"2\"|East Division\n!colspan=\"2\"|West Division\n!Site\n!Attendance\n!MVP\n|-\n|[[2015 American Athletic Conference Championship Game|2015]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[2016 American Athletic Conference Championship Game|2016]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Results by team===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!|Appearances\n!|School\n!|Wins\n!|Losses\n!|Pct.\n|-\n|align=center| 1 ||   ||   ||   ||\n|-\n|align=center| 1 ||   ||   ||   ||\n|} -->\n\n===Rivalries===\nThe American has many rivalries among its member schools, primarily in [[American football|football]]. Some rivalries existed before the conference was established or began play in football. Recent conference realignment in 2005 and 2013 ended \u2013 or temporarily halted \u2013 many rivalries. Before their departure to other conferences, a number of former member schools held longtime rivalries within the conference.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"  style=\"text-align:center; width:95%;\"\n|-\n! Teams !! Rivalry Name !! Trophy !! Meetings !! Began !! Record !! Series leader !! Current Streak\n|-\n| [[East Carolina\u2013UCF football rivalry|East Carolina\u2013UCF]] || \u2014 || \u2014 || 18 || 1991 || 10\u20138\u20130 || East Carolina || UCF won 4\n|-\n| [[Cincinnati\u2013Memphis rivalry#Football|Cincinnati\u2013Memphis]] || \u2014 || \u2014 || 36 || 1966 || 23\u201313\u20130 || Memphis || Memphis won 5\n|-\n| [[Gansz Trophy|Navy\u2013SMU]] || \u2014 ||Gansz Trophy|| 21 || 1930 || 13\u20138\u20130 || Navy || Navy won 1\n|-\n| [[South Florida\u2013UCF rivalry#Football|South Florida\u2013UCF]] || War on I\u20134 || War on I\u20134 Trophy || 11 || 2005 || 6\u20135\u20130 || South Florida || UCF won 3\n|-\n| [[Houston\u2013SMU rivalry#Football|Houston\u2013SMU]] || \u2014 || \u2014 || 35 || 1975 || 21\u201313\u20131 || Houston || SMU won 2\n|-\n| [[Houston\u2013Tulsa football rivalry|Houston\u2013Tulsa]] || The Rivalry || The Gazebo || 44 || 1950 || 25\u201319\u20130 || Houston || Houston won 2\n|}\n\n''Results as of the end of the [[2019 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2019 season]].''\n\n===Bowl games===\nFollowing the 2013 season, the BCS era came to a close and was replaced by the [[College Football Playoff]]. Four teams play in two semifinal games, with the winners advancing to the [[College Football Playoff National Championship]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2013/04/24/college-football-playoff-questions-and-answers/2111419/|title=Questions and answers for the College Football Playoff|last=Wolken |first=Dan |date=April 25, 2013 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=April 25, 2013}}</ref> Six bowl games \u2014 the [[Rose Bowl Game|Rose Bowl]], [[Sugar Bowl]], [[Orange Bowl]], [[Cotton Bowl Classic|Cotton Bowl]], [[Fiesta Bowl]], and [[Peach Bowl]] \u2014 will rotate as hosts for the semifinal games, and host major bowls when they do not host semifinal games (access bowls).\n\nWith the birth of the College Football Playoff, The American lost its automatic qualifying status for one of the major bowls. Instead, one automatic qualifying spot is reserved for the highest ranked team from the \"Group of Five\" conferences \u2013 The American, Conference USA, the Mid-American Conference, Mountain West Conference, and Sun Belt Conference.\n\nAlthough the pick order usually corresponds to the conference standings, the bowls are not required to make their choices strictly according to the won-lost records; many factors influence bowl selections, especially the likely turnout of the team's fans. Picks are made after any applicable College Football Playoff selections. If a team is selected for the one of the access bowls or playoff, the bowl with the No. 2 pick will have the first pick of the remaining teams in the conference.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"  style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%; margin:1em auto;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:50px;\"| Year<ref>{{cite web|title=American Bowl Lineup 2014\u201319|url=http://theamerican.org/sports/2014/4/21/FB_0421143412.aspx?path=football|publisher=sidearm sports|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:265px;\"| Name\n! style=\"width:225px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:225px;\"| Opposing Conference\n|-\n| 2020\u201325\n| [[Cotton Bowl Classic|Cotton]], [[Peach Bowl|Peach]], [[Fiesta Bowl|Fiesta]], or [[College Football Playoff|Playoff]]<ref group=\"note\">If The American's champion is the highest ranked from among the \"Group of Five\" conferences, it will receive a bid to either the Cotton Bowl, the Peach Bowl, or the Fiesta Bowl. If the team is ranked in the top four at the end of the regular season, it will take part in the College Football Playoff.</ref>\n| [[Dallas]], [[Atlanta]], [[Glendale, Arizona|Glendale]], or Playoff Site\n| [[College Football Playoff|CFP At-Large]]\n|-\n| 2020-25\n| [[Fenway Bowl]]\n| [[Boston, Massachusetts]]\n| [[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]]\n|-\n| 2020\u201325\n| [[Military Bowl]]\n| [[Annapolis, Maryland]]\n| [[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]]\n|-\n| 2020/22/24\n| [[Hawaii Bowl|Hawai\u02bbi Bowl]]\n| [[Honolulu|Honolulu, Hawaii]]\n| [[Mountain West Conference|MWC]] or [[BYU Cougars football|BYU]]\n|-\n| 2021/23/25\n| [[Armed Forces Bowl]]\n| [[Fort Worth, Texas]]\n| [[Big 12 Conference|Big 12]] or [[Army Black Knights football|Army]]\n|-\n| 2020\u201325\n| [[Cure Bowl]]\n| [[Orlando, Florida]]\n| [[Sun Belt Conference|Sun Belt]]\n|-\n| 2020\u201325\n| [[Boca Raton Bowl]]\n| [[Boca Raton, Florida]]\n| [[Mid-American Conference|MAC]] or [[Conference USA|C-USA]]\n|-\n| 2020\u201325\n| [[Frisco Bowl]]\n| [[Frisco, Texas]]\n| [[Conference USA|C-USA]], [[Mid-American Conference|MAC]], [[Sun Belt Conference|Sun Belt]] or [[BYU Cougars football|BYU]]\n|-\n| 2020\u201325\n| [[Birmingham Bowl]]\n| [[Birmingham, Alabama]]\n| [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]]\n|-\n| 2020\u201325\n| [[Gasparilla Bowl]]\n| [[Tampa, Florida]]\n| [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]]\n|-\n| 2020\u201325\n| [[First Responder Bowl]]\n| [[Dallas, Texas]]\n| TBD\n|-\n| 2020\u201325\n| [[Myrtle Beach Bowl]]\n| [[Conway, South Carolina]]\n| [[Conference USA|C-USA]], [[Mid-American Conference|MAC]] or [[Sun Belt Conference|Sun Belt]]\n|-\n| 2020\u201325\n| [[New Mexico Bowl]]\n| [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]]\n| TBD\n|}\n\n{{notelist|group=Bowls}}\n\n===Head football coach compensation===\nThe total pay of head coaches includes university and non-university compensation. This includes base salary, income from contracts, foundation supplements, bonuses and media and radio pay.<ref name=\"hcsalaries\">{{cite web|title=College Football Head Coach Salaries|url=https://sports.usatoday.com/ncaa/salaries/|website=USA TODAY Sports|accessdate=December 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191231122451/https://sports.usatoday.com/ncaa/salaries|archive-date=December 31, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"  style=\"text-align:center; margin:1em auto;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:50px;\"| Conf. <br> Rank\n! style=\"width:200px;\"| University\n! style=\"width:140px;\"| Head Coach\n! style=\"width:120px;\"| Salary<ref name=\"hcsalaries\"/>\n|-\n| 1\n| {{sort|Houston|[[Houston Cougars football|University of Houston]]}}\n| {{sortname|Dana|Holgorsen}}\n| $3,700,000\n|-\n| 2\n| {{sort|South Florida|[[South Florida Bulls football|University of South Florida]]}}\n| {{sortname|Jeff|Scott}}{{sup|\u2020}}\n| $2,500,000\n|-\n| 3\n| {{sort|Naval Academy|[[Navy Midshipmen football|United States Naval Academy]]}}\n| {{sortname|Ken|Niumatalolo}}\n| $2,316,000\n|-\n| 4\n| {{sort|Cincinnati|[[Cincinnati Bearcats football|University of Cincinnati]]}}\n| {{sortname|Luke|Fickell}}\n| $2,300,000\