 (since 1982), with [[UConn Huskies women's basketball|UConn]] winning 11 national championships under head coach [[Geno Auriemma]] since 1995. Women's national championship tournaments prior to 1982 were run by the [[AIAW Women's Basketball Tournament|AIAW]].\n\n===All-time school records by winning percentage===\nThis list goes through the 2016\u201317 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Records Through 2012\u201313|url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/w_basketball_RB/2014/DI.pdf|publisher=[[NCAA]]|accessdate=March 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center; margin:1em auto; font-size:95%; width:90%;\"<!-- NOTE: Final Fours includes all divisions, national championships includes pre-NCAA and AIAW -->\n|-\n! No. !! Team !! Records !! Win Pct.  !! The American<br />Tournament <br> Championships !!  The American <br> Regular Season <br> Championships !! Final Fours !! National <br> Championships\n|-\n| 1 || [[Memphis Tigers women's basketball|Memphis]] || 781\u2013590{{efn|group=wbrec|Record since the 1972\u201373 season, considered by Memphis to be the start of its \"modern era\" of women's basketball.}} || {{winpct|781|590}} || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| 2 || [[Tulane Green Wave women's basketball|Tulane]] || 684\u2013534 || {{winpct|684|534}} || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| 3 || [[Temple Owls women's basketball|Temple]] || 806\u2013653\u20133 || {{winpct|806|653|3}} || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| 4 || [[SMU Mustangs women's basketball|SMU]] || 630\u2013534 || {{winpct|630|534}} || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| 5 || [[East Carolina Pirates women's basketball|East Carolina]] || 705\u2013600 || {{winpct|705|600}} || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| 6 || [[Houston Cougars women's basketball|Houston]] || 650\u2013603 || {{winpct|650|603}} || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| 7 || [[Cincinnati Bearcats women's basketball|Cincinnati]] || 636\u2013628 || {{winpct|636|628}} || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| 8 || [[South Florida Bulls women's basketball|Sout