{"title_page": "Geoff Webster", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix          =\n| name                      = Geoff Webster\n| honorific_suffix          = \n| image                     = <!-- just the name, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = Geoffrey B. Webster<ref name=Electoral />\n| birth_date                = 1959<ref name=BBCa />\n| birth_place               = \n| death_date                = \n| death_place               = \n| residence                 = \n| nationality               = British\n| education                 = \n| alma_mater                = \n| occupation                = Newspaper editor\n| years_active              = \n| employer                  = [[The Sun (United Kingdom)|''The Sun'' newspaper]]<br />[[News UK|News Corp UK]]\n| organization              = \n| known_for                 = Arrested and charged as part of [[Operation Elveden#Arrests|Operation Elveden]]\n| predecessor               = \n| successor                 = \n| criminal_charge           = [[Conspiracy (crime)#Statutory offence|Conspiring to commit misconduct in a public office]] (section 1(1) of the Criminal Law Act 1977).<ref name=BBCb /><ref name=\"CPS-charge\" />\n| criminal_penalty          = \n| criminal_status           = \n| spouse                    = [[Alison Webster (photographer)|Alison Webster]]\n| children                  = \n| parents                   = \n| awards                    = \n| website                   = \n| signature                 = \n| signature_size            = \n| signature_alt             = \n| baptism_date              = \n}}\n\n'''Geoff Webster''' (born '''Geoffrey B. Webster''';<ref name=Electoral /> 1959)<ref name=BBCa /> is the deputy editor of ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' newspaper in the UK (currently suspended due to criminal charges brought under [[Operation Elveden#Arrests|Operation Elveden]]).<ref name=BBCb /><ref name=\"CPS-charge\" /><ref name=Deadline />\n\n== Move to the ''Sun'' newspaper ==\nIn 2003 the deputy editor of the ''[[News of the World]]'', [[Rebekah Brooks]], was appointed editor of the ''Sun'' newspaper. Shortly after arriving Brooks moved Webster from his job as associate editor/head of pictures at the News of the World, appointing him associate editor at the Sun, effectively making him \"third in command\" on the paper.<ref name=Wade />\n\n== Promotion ==\nWebster was promoted to joint deputy editor of the ''Sun'', along with Simon Cosyns, when [[David Dinsmore]] replaced Brooks as editor in 2009.<ref name=Promotion />\n\n== Criminal charges ==\n{{wikinews|Five arrested over police payments at News International}}\nWebster was arrested<ref name=\"Arrested\">{{cite news|last=Batty|first=David|title=Senior Sun journalists arrested in police payments probe|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/feb/11/sun-journalists-arrested|accessdate=29 August 2013|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=11 February 2012}}</ref> and charged with [[Conspiracy (crime)#Statutory offence|conspiring to commit misconduct in a public office]]<ref name=BBCb /><ref name=Decision /> as part of [[Operation Elveden#Arrests|Operation Elveden]]. One of the charges relates to an alleged payment of \u00a36,500 to a [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] official, with a further \u00a31,500 allegedly going to another public official.<ref name=\"CPS-charge\" /><ref name=MOD />\n\nWebster's arrest in February 2012 prompted [[Rupert Murdoch]] to fly to London to reassure the staff that he would not be closing down the newspaper.<ref name=Arrested /> Writing in ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Roy Greenslade]] described Murdoch's meeting with the staff:\n<blockquote>\"Though some reports suggested soon after the 6 March meeting that he [Rupert Murdoch] had won over the assembled staff, I was told the opposite. ... They were not in the least bit mollified by what he had to say. ... It was a hugely emotional occasion. Former managing editor [[Graham Dudman]] \u2013 the major spokesman on behalf of his colleagues \u2013 eventually broke down in tears. This followed the reading \u2013 by [[Dear Deidre|agony aunt Deidre Sanders]] \u2013 of a letter written by [[Alison Webster (photographer)|Alison Webster]], the Page 3 photographer who is married to deputy editor Geoff Webster (who attended the meeting).\"<ref name=Greenslade>{{cite news|last=Greenslade|first=Roy|title=Greenslade Blog: Why Rupert Murdoch tape was leaked \u2013 tearful journalists were angry|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2013/jul/04/news-corporation-rupert-murdoch|accessdate=29 August 2013|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=4 July 2013}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nWebster was supported by several colleagues, and his wife, when he appeared in court.<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Caroll|first=Lisa|title=Sun staff show support as deputy editor appears in court|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2013/mar/26/sun-deputy-editor|accessdate=29 August 2013| newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=26 March 2013}}</ref> He pleaded not guilty at the [[Old Bailey]] and was given unconditional bail.<ref name=BBCa /> On 20 March 2015, Webster was cleared of charges that he had signed off illegal payments.<ref name=\"BBC News 20 March 2015\">{{cite web | title= Sun journalists cleared in payments trial|url=  https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-31986754| author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->| website= BBC News | accessdate= 20 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Biography|Journalism}}\n*[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]] newspaper\n*[[Operation Elveden]]\n*[[Conspiracy (crime)#Statutory offence|Section 1(1) of the Criminal Law Act 1977]], conspiring to commit misconduct in public office.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em|refs=\n<ref name=Electoral>{{cite web|title=Electoral Roll records from 2009\u201313|url=http://www.192.com/atoz/people/webster/geoffrey/tn17/1427391211/|publisher=192.com|accessdate=7 September 2013}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"BBCa\">{{cite news|last=BBC|first=news|title=Sun deputy editor Geoff Webster denies 'plotting misconduct'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-23345686|accessdate=29 August 2013|newspaper=BBC news|date=17 July 2013}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"BBCb\">{{cite news|last=BBC|first=news|title=The Sun's Geoff Webster charged over payments to officials|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-21860440|accessdate=29 August 2013|newspaper=BBC news|date=20 March 2013}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"CPS-charge\">{{cite web|title=Operation Elveden: CPS Charging Decision Operation Elveden: CPS Charging Decision|url=http://www.cps.gov.uk/news/latest_news/operation_elveden_cps_charging_decision/|publisher=Crown Prosecution Service|accessdate=9 September 2013|date=20 March 2013|quote=We have concluded, following a careful review of the evidence, that Geoff Webster, who at the time of the alleged offending was Deputy Editor of The Sun newspaper, should be charged with two offences of conspiring to commit misconduct in public office, contrary to section 1(1) of the Criminal Law Act 1977.}}</ref> \n<ref name=Deadline>{{cite news|last=Tartagione|first=Nancy|title=Former editor of Rupert Murdoch's The Sun charged in corruption probe|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/03/former-editor-of-rupert-murdochs-the-sun-charged-in-corruption-probe/|accessdate=21 October 2013|newspaper=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline London]]|date=20 March 2013}}</ref>\n<ref name=Wade>{{cite news|last=Byrne|first=Ciar|title=Wade puts Webster in the picture|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2003/jan/23/sun.pressandpublishing|accessdate=7 September 2013|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=23 January 2003}}</ref>\n<ref name=Promotion>{{cite news|last=Sweney|first=Mark|title=The Sun appoints Simon Cosyns and Geoff Webster as joint deputy editors|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/sep/07/the-sun-deputy-editors|accessdate=7 September 2013|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=7 September 2009}}</ref> \n<ref name=\"Arrested\">{{cite news|last=Batty|first=David|title=Senior Sun journalists arrested in police payments probe|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/feb/11/sun-journalists-arrested|accessdate=29 August 2013|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=11 February 2012}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Decision\">{{cite news|last=Cusick|first=James|title=The Sun's deputy editor Geoff Webster charged over illicit payments to officials|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/the-suns-deputy-editor-geoff-webster-charged-over-illicit-payments-to-officials-8542116.html|accessdate=29 August 2013|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=20 March 2013}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"MOD\">{{cite news|last1=O'Carroll|first1=Lisa|last2=Laville|first2=Sandra|title= Sun deputy editor charged over alleged payments to public officials|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2013/mar/20/sun-deputy-editor-charged-geoff-webster?guni=Article:in%20body%20link|accessdate=29 August 2013|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=20 March 2013|quote=One charge Webster faces relates to a Ministry of Defence official for whom payment of \u00a36,500 was allegedly authorised by him on behalf of another Sun journalist.}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box|title=Joint Deputy Editor of ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]''|years=2009\u2013now(with Simon Coysns)|before=[[Dominic Mohan]]|}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Webster, Geoffrey}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People associated with the News International phone hacking scandal]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:News of the World people]]\n[[Category:The Sun (United Kingdom) people]]\n\n\n{{UK-journalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix          =\n| name                      = Geoff Webster\n| honorific_suffix          = \n| image                     = <!-- just the name, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = Geoffrey B. Webster<ref name=Electoral />\n| birth_date                = 1959<ref name=BBCa />\n| birth_place               = \n| death_date                = \n| death_place               = \n| residence                 = \n| nationality               = British\n| education                 = \n| alma_mater                = \n| occupation                = Newspaper editor\n| years_active              = \n| employer                  = [[The Sun (United Kingdom)|''The Sun'' newspaper]]<br />[[News UK|News Corp UK]]\n| organization              = \n| known_for                 = Arrested and charged as part of [[Operation Elveden#Arrests|Operation Elveden]]\n| predecessor               = \n| successor                 = \n| criminal_charge           = [[Conspiracy (crime)#Statutory offence|Conspiring to commit misconduct in a public office]] (section 1(1) of the Criminal Law Act 1977).<ref name=BBCb /><ref name=\"CPS-charge\" />\n| criminal_penalty          = \n| criminal_status           = \n| spouse                    = [[Alison Webster (photographer)|Alison Webster]]\n| children                  = \n| parents                   = \n| awards                    = \n| website                   = \n| signature                 = \n| signature_size            = \n| signature_alt             = \n| baptism_date              = \n}}\n\n'''Geoff Webster''' (born '''Geoffrey B. Webster''';<ref name=Electoral /> 1959)<ref name=BBCa /> is the deputy editor of ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' newspaper in the UK (currently suspended due to criminal charges brought under [[Operation Elveden#Arrests|Operation Elveden]]).<ref name=BBCb /><ref name=\"CPS-charge\" /><ref name=Deadline />\n\n== Move to the ''Sun'' newspaper ==\nIn 2003 the deputy editor of the ''[[News of the World]]'', [[Rebekah Brooks]], was appointed editor of the ''Sun'' newspaper. Shortly after arriving Brooks moved Webster from his job as associate editor/head of pictures at the News of the World, appointing him associate editor at the Sun, effectively making him \"third in command\" on the paper.<ref name=Wade />\n\n== Promotion ==\nWebster was promoted to joint deputy editor of the ''Sun'', along with Simon Cosyns, when [[David Dinsmore]] replaced Brooks as editor in 2009.<ref name=Promotion />\n\n== Criminal charges ==\n{{wikinews|Five arrested over police payments at News International}}\nWebster was arrested<ref name=\"Arrested\">{{cite news|last=Batty|first=David|title=Senior Sun journalists arrested in police payments probe|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/feb/11/sun-journalists-arrested|accessdate=29 August 2013|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=11 February 2012}}</ref> and charged with [[Conspiracy (crime)#Statutory offence|conspiring to commit misconduct in a public office]]<ref name=BBCb /><ref name=Decision /> as part of [[Operation Elveden#Arrests|Operation Elveden]]. One of the charges relates to an alleged payment of \u00a36,500 to a [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] official, with a further \u00a31,500 allegedly going to another public official.<ref name=\"CPS-charge\" /><ref name=MOD />\n\nWebster's arrest in February 2012 prompted [[Rupert Murdoch]] to fly to London to reassure the staff that he would not be closing down the newspaper.<ref name=Arrested /> Writing in ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Roy Greenslade]] described Murdoch's meeting with the staff:\n<blockquote>\"Though some reports suggested soon after the 6 March meeting that he [Rupert Murdoch] had won over the assembled staff, I was told the opposite. ... They were not in the least bit mollified by what he had to say. ... It was a hugely emotional occasion. Former managing editor [[Graham Dudman]] \u2013 the major spokesman on behalf of his colleagues \u2013 eventually broke down in tears. This followed the reading \u2013 by [[Dear Deidre|agony aunt Deidre Sanders]] \u2013 of a letter written by [[Alison Webster (photographer)|Alison Webster]], the Page 3 photographer who is married to deputy editor Geoff Webster (who attended the meeting).\"<ref name=Greenslade>{{cite news|last=Greenslade|first=Roy|title=Greenslade Blog: Why Rupert Murdoch tape was leaked \u2013 tearful journalists were angry|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2013/jul/04/news-corporation-rupert-murdoch|accessdate=29 August 2013|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=4 July 2013}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nWebster was supported by several colleagues, and his wife, when he appeared in court.<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Caroll|first=Lisa|title=Sun staff show support as deputy editor appears in court|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2013/mar/26/sun-deputy-editor|accessdate=29 August 2013| newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=26 March 2013}}</ref> He pleaded not guilty at the [[Old Bailey]] and was given unconditional bail.<ref name=BBCa /> On 20 March 2015, Webster was cleared of charges that he had signed off illegal payments.<ref name=\"BBC News 20 March 2015\">{{cite web | title= Sun journalists cleared in payments trial|url=  https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-31986754| author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->| website= BBC News | accessdate= 20 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Biography|Journalism}}\n*[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]] newspaper\n*[[Operation Elveden]]\n*[[Conspiracy (crime)#Statutory offence|Section 1(1) of the Criminal Law Act 1977]], conspiring to commit misconduct in public office.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em|refs=\n<ref name=Electoral>{{cite web|title=Electoral Roll records from 2009\u201313|url=http://www.192.com/atoz/people/webster/geoffrey/tn17/1427391211/|publisher=192.com|accessdate=7 September 2013}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"BBCa\">{{cite news|last=BBC|first=news|title=Sun deputy editor Geoff Webster denies 'plotting misconduct'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-23345686|accessdate=29 August 2013|newspaper=BBC news|date=17 July 2013}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"BBCb\">{{cite news|last=BBC|first=news|title=The Sun's Geoff Webster charged over payments to officials|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-21860440|accessdate=29 August 2013|newspaper=BBC news|date=20 March 2013}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"CPS-charge\">{{cite web|title=Operation Elveden: CPS Charging Decision Operation Elveden: CPS Charging Decision|url=http://www.cps.gov.uk/news/latest_news/operation_elveden_cps_charging_decision/|publisher=Crown Prosecution Service|accessdate=9 September 2013|date=20 March 2013|quote=We have concluded, following a careful review of the evidence, that Geoff Webster, who at the time of the alleged offending was Deputy Editor of The Sun newspaper, should be charged with two offences of conspiring to commit misconduct in public office, contrary to section 1(1) of the Criminal Law Act 1977.}}</ref> \n<ref name=Deadline>{{cite news|last=Tartagione|first=Nancy|title=Former editor of Rupert Murdoch's The Sun charged in corruption probe|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/03/former-editor-of-rupert-murdochs-the-sun-charged-in-corruption-probe/|accessdate=21 October 2013|newspaper=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline London]]|date=20 March 2013}}</ref>\n<ref name=Wade>{{cite news|last=Byrne|first=Ciar|title=Wade puts Webster in the picture|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2003/jan/23/sun.pressandpublishing|accessdate=7 September 2013|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=23 January 2003}}</ref>\n<ref name=Promotion>{{cite news|last=Sweney|first=Mark|title=The Sun appoints Simon Cosyns and Geoff Webster as joint deputy editors|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/sep/07/the-sun-deputy-editors|accessdate=7 September 2013|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=7 September 2009}}</ref> \n<ref name=\"Arrested\">{{cite news|last=Batty|first=David|title=Senior Sun journalists arrested in police payments probe|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/feb/11/sun-journalists-arrested|accessdate=29 August 2013|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=11 February 2012}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Decision\">{{cite news|last=Cusick|first=James|title=The Sun's deputy editor Geoff Webster charged over illicit payments to officials|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/the-suns-deputy-editor-geoff-webster-charged-over-illicit-payments-to-officials-8542116.html|accessdate=29 August 2013|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=20 March 2013}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"MOD\">{{cite news|last1=O'Carroll|first1=Lisa|last2=Laville|first2=Sandra|title= Sun deputy editor charged over alleged payments to public officials|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2013/mar/20/sun-deputy-editor-charged-geoff-webster?guni=Article:in%20body%20link|accessdate=29 August 2013|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=20 March 2013|quote=One charge Webster faces relates to a Ministry of Defence official for whom payment of \u00a36,500 was allegedly authorised by him on behalf of another Sun journalist.}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box|title=Joint Deputy Editor of ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]''|years=2009\u2013now(with Simon Coysns)|before=[[Dominic Mohan]]|}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Webster, Geoffrey}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People associated with the News International phone hacking scandal]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:News of the World people]]\n[[Category:The Sun (United Kingdom) people]]\n\n\n{{UK-journalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geoff_Webster"}
{"title_page": "Skelmersdale railway station", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n<br />{{Infobox UK disused station                    \n|name        = Skelmersdale\n| image_name  = Skelmersdale railway station.jpg\n| caption     = \n|line        = [[Skelmersdale branch]]<!-- intentional -->\n|original    = [[East Lancashire Railway 1844\u20131859|East Lancashire Railway]]\n|pregroup    = [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]]\n|postgroup   = [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]]\n|locale      = [[Skelmersdale]]\n|borough     = [[West Lancashire]]\n|platforms   = 2{{sfn|James|2004|p=32}}\n|years       = 1 March 1858\n|events      = Opened as ''Blaguegate''\n| years1      = 1 August 1874\n| events1     = Renamed ''Skelmersdale''\n| years2      = 5 November 1956\n| events2     = Closed (passenger services)\n| years3      = 4 November 1963\n| events3     = Closed (all services)\n|coordinates = {{coord|53.5506|-2.8105|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n|gridref     = SD464063\n|events4=Plans to rebuild the station on the Wigan to Kirkby line are put to the government <ref>https://www.lancs.live/news/lancashire-news/plans-skelmersdale-train-station-move-16294321</ref>|years4=17 May 2019}}\n{{Skelmersdale Branch|collapse=yes}}\n\n'''Skelmersdale railway station''' was a station located on the [[Skelmersdale branch]] at [[Skelmersdale]], [[England]]. The station was originally named '''Blague Gate''', having its name changed to Skelmersdale on 8 August 1874 and carried passengers from 1858 to 1956.<ref name=\"skemheritage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.skemheritage.org.uk/ackerley/railway.htm|title=The coming of the railway|first=Dave|last=Ackerley|work=Skelmersdale Heritage Society|accessdate=5 May 2008}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Hartford, Northwich and Rainford RJD 92.jpg|thumb|left|A 1908 [[Railway Clearing House]] Junction Diagram showing (lower right) railways in the vicinity of Skelmersdale]]\nThe station was one of several built by the [[East Lancashire Railway 1844-1859|East Lancashire Railway]] on their branch line from Ormskirk to [[Rainford railway station|Rainford Junction]].  It opened on 1 March 1858, but after a year became part of the [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]] system when the ELR was taken over by that company.  The station consisted of two platforms with the main building on the northbound side.  A wooden signal box was provided to control the adjacent [[level crossing]], passing loop and nearby goods yard.  The line towards Ormskirk was subsequently doubled in 1875, the year after the station was renamed.\n\nThroughout its life the route operated as a self-contained branch, though connections were available for {{rws|Preston}}, [[Liverpool Exchange railway station|Liverpool]] & Blackpool at Ormskirk and for {{rws|St Helens Central}}, {{rws|Wigan Wallgate}} and [[Manchester Victoria railway station|Manchester Victoria]] at Rainford.  The service was also generous, with the L&Y running a steam [[railmotor]] service of 19 trains per day in each direction from 1906.  A similar pattern continued after the route became part of the [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]] in January 1923, but increasing road competition after World War II and the subsequent [[nationalisation]] of the railways in 1948 saw traffic levels decline.\n\nThe station was closed to passenger traffic by the [[British Transport Commission]] on 5 November 1956,<ref>{{Butt-Stations |page=213 }}</ref> with the line south to Rainford closing completely on 16 November 1961 and the rest on 4 November 1963, when goods traffic at the station ceased.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/s/skelmersdale/index.shtml|title=Disused Stations \u2013 Skelmersdale|work=Disused Stations|accessdate=23 October 2013}}</ref>  The track was lifted in 1968 and station was demolished soon afterwards; the B5312 road (known as ''Railway Road'') now passes through the site.\n\nIronically this was done just as the town was undergoing a significant increase in population levels and associated housing development, having been designated as one of the second wave of [[New towns in the United Kingdom|new towns]] in 1961 (it was chosen, along with [[Runcorn]] as an overspill town for Liverpool).\n\n==Reopening proposals==\n\nSkelmersdale has been described as the largest town in North-West England that doesn't have a railway station,<ref>{{cite web|title=A station back in Skelmersdale|url=http://www.railfuture.org.uk/A+Station+Back+in+Skelmersdale|website=railfuture|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> although Leigh in Greater Manchester, which also has no station is larger.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.wigan.gov.uk/Docs/PDF/Council/Council-statistics-and-demographics/Census2011PopulationandHouseholdEstimatesforWards.pdf|format=PDF|title=Census 2011: Population and Household Estimates for Wards|publisher=[[Wigan Council]]|accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref> There have been many discussions about reopening a railway station in Skelmersdale. This would require a three-mile rail restoration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk/pa/cm200203/cmselect/cmtran/782/782ap38.htm|title=House of Commons \u2013 Transport \u2013 Appendices to the Minutes of Evidence|work=parliament.uk|accessdate=1 January 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311054123/http://www.parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk/pa/cm200203/cmselect/cmtran/782/782ap38.htm|archivedate=11 March 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In January 2009, the ''[[Liverpool Echo]]'' newspaper reported that recommendations have been put to councillors to endorse the \u00a360m plan to build a new railway station in Skelmersdale, reconnecting the town with Liverpool.<ref name=\"livecho_\u00a360m_plans\">{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/liverpool-news/local-news/2009/01/22/40m-rail-link-plans-are-backed-100252-22750057/ |title=\u00a340m rail link plans are backed |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |date=22 January 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2009, the [[Association of Train Operating Companies]], in its [[Connecting Communities: Expanding Access to the Rail Network|Expanding Access to the Rail Network]] report, called for funding for the reopening of this station as part of a \u00a3500m scheme to open 33 stations on 14 lines closed in the [[Beeching Axe]], including seven new parkway stations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/8099912.stm|title=BBC NEWS \u2013 England \u2013 Operators call for new rail lines|accessdate=15 June 2009 | date=15 June 2009|work=BBC News}}</ref> The report proposes extending the line from {{rws|Ormskirk}} by laying 3 miles of new single track along the previous route to the town, at a cost estimated to be in the region of \u00a331million. The route is largely intact, though a deviation north of [[Westhead]] would be required. The proposed station would be on the north west corner of town near the Skelmersdale Ring Road, right next to where the old station once was.{{ATOCConnectingCommunitiesReportS10|page=20}} A feasibility study on the project jointly funded by [[Merseytravel]], [[Merseyrail]], Lancashire County Council & West Lancs Borough Council was due to begin in the autumn of 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.osadvertiser.co.uk/news/skelmersdale-news/2013/07/11/skelmersdale-railway-feasibility-study-80904-33592194/ |title=Skelmersdale railway feasibility study|work=Ormskirk & Skelmersdale Advertiser|accessdate=23 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Lancashire County Council]] approved the initiation of a more detailed evaluation on 1 June 2015.<ref name=spv>{{cite web|url=http://www.southportvisiter.co.uk/news/southport-west-lancs/skelmersdale-railway-plans-right-track-9370775|title=Skelmersdale railway plans on the right track |work=Southport Visiter|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref> This option selection process will take the project to completing Network Rail's [[Network Rail#The GRIP process|GRIP]] ''stage 3'' level of development in January 2017.<ref name=spv /><ref name=rail>{{cite web|url=http://www.railmagazine.com/news/network/2015/06/03/skelmersdale-link-moves-towards-grip3|title=Skelmersdale link moves towards GRIP3|work=[[RAIL (magazine)|RAIL]]|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref> The evaluation is to be developed in partnership with [[Network Rail]] and Merseytravel.<ref name=rail /> Network Rail has suggested a construction date commencing in April 2021, with services beginning from December 2023,<ref name=rail /> once the single option development and detailed design stages in the GRIP process have been achieved. The likely route for the new link is southwards to join the [[Kirkby branch line]] between Upholland and Rainford rather than the original plans to go north via Ormskirk, so as to enable trains to travel to Wigan & Manchester as well as to Liverpool.<ref name=spv />\n\nIn February 2017 Lancashire County Council confirmed that the preferred site for Skelmersdale railway station was the former site of [[Glenburn Sports College]]/Westbank Campus.<ref>[http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/news/details.aspx?Id=PR17/0032 Preferred Site Identified for Skelmersdale Railway Station] Lancashire County Council</ref> County Council Transport portfolio holder John Fillis said that the site \"is big enough to provide a high quality station with scope to expand to meet future demand.\".<ref>[http://www.southportvisiter.co.uk/news/southport-west-lancs/preferred-site-identified-skelmersdale-railway-12548052 Preferred site identified for Skelmersdale railway station] Southport Visiter</ref> By September, Merseytravel announced that they would be committing \u00a3765,000 to the study into the reopening, estimating that the station could be open within a decade with a lot of additional funding. Merseytravel's plan would also see a new station built at [[Headbolt Lane]] in Kirkby. It has been proposed a new station at Skelmersdale would act as the terminus for Merseyrail's [[Northern Line (Merseyrail)|Northern Line]], with connections available to Wigan and Manchester. Initial estimates suggest that the scheme could cost around \u00a3300 million to develop.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Houghton|first1=Alistair|title=Skelmersdale rail link moves step closer as \u00a35m funding revealed|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/skelmersdale-rail-link-moves-step-13639557|website=liverpoolecho|accessdate=19 September 2017|date=18 September 2017}}</ref>  On page 36 of the [[Liverpool City Region Combined Authority]], Long Term Rail Strategy document of October 2017, it states that Merseytravel is currently working with Lancashire County Council and Network Rail to develop a plan to extend the Merseyrail network from Kirkby through to Skelmersdale, with work completed in 2019. They are considering 3rd rail electrification and other alternatives with a new station at Headbolt Lane to serve the Northwood area of Kirkby. The document on page 37 states two trials of electric 3rd rail/battery trains will be undertaken in 2020, this is one of the \"alternatives\".  <ref>http://moderngov.merseytravel.uk.net/documents/s21686/Enc.%201%20for%20Updated%20Long%20term%20Rail%20Strategy.pdf</ref>\n\nLancashire County Coucil approved a plan in May 2019 to commission an outline business case into reopening the station which will be presented to the government.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Faulkner |first1=Paul |title=Plans for Skelmersdale train station move one step closer |url=https://www.lancs.live/news/lancashire-news/plans-skelmersdale-train-station-move-16294321 |accessdate=31 August 2019 |work=Lancs Live |date=17 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{citation |last=James |first=David |title=Lancashire's Lost Railways |publisher=Stenlake Publishing |year=2004 |isbn=1 84033 288 3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.subbrit.org.uk/sb-sites/stations/s/skelmersdale/index.shtml Description via ''Disused Stations UK'']\n* [http://www.skemheritage.org.uk/ackerley/railway.htm The coming of the railway]\n* [http://www.npemap.org.uk/tiles/map.html#346,405,1 The station on an old O.S. Map via ''npemaps'']\n\n{{Disused Rail Start}}\n{{Rail line\n|previous=[[Westhead Halt railway station|Westhead Halt]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> \n|next=[[White Moss Level Crossing railway station|White Moss Level Crossing Halt]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> \n|route=[[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]]<br><small>[[Skelmersdale branch]]</small> \n|col={{LYR colour}} }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Merseyrail Northern Line}}\n{{Closed stations Lancashire}}\n{{Proposed rail infrastructure projects in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in the Borough of West Lancashire]]\n[[Category:Former Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1858]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1956]]\n[[Category:Proposed railway stations in England]]\n[[Category:Skelmersdale]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station                    \n|name        = Skelmersdale\n| image_name  = Skelmersdale railway station.jpg\n| caption     = \n|line        = [[Skelmersdale branch]]<!-- intentional -->\n|original    = [[East Lancashire Railway 1844\u20131859|East Lancashire Railway]]\n|pregroup    = [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]]\n|postgroup   = [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]]\n|locale      = [[Skelmersdale]]\n|borough     = [[West Lancashire]]\n|platforms   = 2{{sfn|James|2004|p=32}}\n|years       = 1 March 1858\n|events      = Opened as ''Blaguegate''\n| years1      = 1 August 1874\n| events1     = Renamed ''Skelmersdale''\n| years2      = 5 November 1956\n| events2     = Closed (passenger services)\n| years3      = 4 November 1963\n| events3     = Closed (all services)\n|coordinates = {{coord|