[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]] in January 1923, but increasing road competition after World War II and the subsequent [[nationalisation]] of the railways in 1948 saw traffic levels decline.\n\nThe station was closed to passenger traffic by the [[British Transport Commission]] on 5 November 1956,<ref>{{Butt-Stations |page=213 }}</ref> with the line south to Rainford closing completely on 16 November 1961 and the rest on 4 November 1963, when goods traffic at the station ceased.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/s/skelmersdale/index.shtml|title=Disused Stations \u2013 Skelmersdale|work=Disused Stations|accessdate=23 October 2013}}</ref>  The track was lifted in 1968 and station was demolished soon afterwards; the B5312 road (known as ''Railway Road'') now passes through the site.\n\nIronically this was done just as the town was undergoing a significant increase in population levels and associated housing development, having been designated as one of the second wave of [[New towns in the United Kingdom|new towns]] in 1961 (it was chosen, along with [[Runcorn]] as an overspill town for Liverpool).\n\n==Reopening proposals==\n\nSkelmersdale has been described as the largest town in North-West England that doesn't have a railway station,<ref>{{cite web|title=A station back in Skelmersdale|url=http://www.railfuture.org.uk/A+Station+Back+in+Skelmersdale|website=railfuture|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> although Leigh in Greater Manchester, which also has no station is larger.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.wigan.gov.uk/Docs/PDF/Council/Council-statistics-and-demographics/Census2011PopulationandHouseholdEstimatesforWards.pdf|format=PDF|title=Census 2011: Population and Household Estimates for Wards|publisher=[[Wigan Council]]|accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref> There have been many discussions about reopening a railway station in Skelmersdale. This would require a three-mile rail restoration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk/pa/cm200203/cmselect/cmtran/782/782ap38.htm|title=House of Commons \u2013 Transport \u2013 Appendices to the Minutes of Evidence|work=parliament.uk|accessdate=1 January 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311054123/http://www.parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk/pa/cm200203/cmselect/cmtran/782/782ap38.htm|archivedate=11 March 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In January 2009, the ''[[Liverpool Echo]]'' newspaper reported that recommendations have been put to councillors to endorse the \u00a360m plan to build a new railway station in Skelmersdale, reconnecting the town with Liverpool.<ref name=\"livecho_\u00a360m_plans\">{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/liverpool-news/local-news/2009/01/22/40m-rail-link-plans-are-backed-100252-22750057/ |title=\u00a340m rail link plans are backed |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |date=22 January 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2009, the [[Association of Train Operating Companies]], in its [[Connecting Communities: Expanding Access to the Rail Network|Expanding Access to the Rail Network]] report, called for funding for the reopening of this station as part of a \u00a3500m scheme to open 33 stations on 14 lines closed in the [[Beeching Axe]], including seven new parkway stations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/8099912.stm|title=BBC NEWS \u2013 England \u2013 Operators call for new rail lines|accessdate=15 June 2009 | date=15 June 2009|work=BBC News}}</ref> The report proposes extending the line from {{rws|Ormskirk}} by laying 3 miles of new single track along the previous route to the town, at a cost estimated to be in the region of \u00a331million. The route is largely intact, though a deviation north of [[Westhead]] would be required. The proposed station would be on the north west corner of town near the Skelmersdale Ring Road, right next to where the old station once was.{{ATOCConnectingCommunitiesReportS10|page=20}} A feasibility study on the project jointly funded by [[Merseytravel]], [[Merseyrail]], Lancashire County Council & West Lancs Borough Council was due to begin in the autumn of 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.osadvertiser.co.uk/news/skelmersdale-news/2013/07/11/skelmersdale-railway-feasibility-study-80904-33592194/ |title=Skelmersdale railway feasibility study|work=Ormskirk & Skelmersdale Advertiser|accessdate=23 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Lancashire County Council]] approved the initiation of a more detailed evaluation on 1 June 2015.<ref name=spv>{{cite web|url=http://www.southportvisiter.co.uk/news/southport-west-lancs/skelmersdale-railway-plans-right-track-9370775|title=Skelmersdale railway plans on the right track |work=Southport Visiter|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref> This option selection process will take the project to completing Network Rail's [[Network Rail#The GRIP process|GRIP]] ''stage 3'' level of development in January 2017.<ref name=spv /><ref name=rail>{{cite web|url=http://www.railmagazine.com/news/network/2015/06/03/skelmersdale-link-moves-towards-grip3|title=Skelmersdale link moves towards GRIP3|work=[[RAIL (magazine)|RAIL]]|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref> The evaluation is to be developed in partnership with [[Network Rail]] and Merseytravel.<ref name=rail /> Network Rail has suggested a construction date commencing in April 2021, with services beginning from December 2023,<ref name=rail /> once the single option development and detailed design stages in the GRIP process have been achieved. The likely route for the new link is southwards to join the [[Kirkby branch line]] between Upholland and Rainford rather than the original plans to go north via Ormskirk, so as to enable trains to travel to Wigan & Manchester as well as to Liverpool.<ref name=spv />\n\nIn February 2017 Lancashire County Council confirmed that the preferred site for Skelmersdale railway station was the former site of [[Glenburn Sports College]]/Westbank Campus.<ref>[http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/news/details.aspx?Id=PR17/0032 Preferred Site Identified for Skelmersdale Railway Station] Lancashire County Council</ref> County Council Transport portfolio holder John Fillis said that the site \"is big enough to provide a high quality station with scope to expand to meet future demand.\".<ref>[http://www.southportvisiter.co.uk/news/southport-west-lancs/preferred-site-identified-skelmersdale-railway-12548052 Preferred site identified for Skelmersdale railway station] Southport Visiter</ref> By September, Merseytravel announced that they would be committing \u00a3765,000 to the study into the reopening, estimating that the station could be open within a decade with a lot of additional funding. Merseytravel's plan would also see a new station built at [[Headbolt Lane]] in Kirkby. It has been proposed a new station at Skelmersdale would act as the terminus for Merseyrail's [[Northern Line (Merseyrail)|Northern Line]], with connections available to Wigan and Manchester. Initial estimates suggest that the scheme could cost around \u00a3300 million to develop.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Houghton|first1=Alistair|title=Skelmersdale rail link moves step closer as \u00a35m funding revealed|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/skelmersdale-rail-link-moves-step-13639557|website=liverpoolecho|accessdate=19 September 2017|date=18 September 2017}}</ref>  On page 36 of the [[Liverpool City Region Combined Authority]], Long Term Rail Strategy document of October 2017, it states that Merseytravel is currently working with Lancashire County Council and Network Rail to develop a plan to extend the Merseyrail network from Kirkby through to Skelmersdale, with work completed in 2019. They are considering 3rd rail electrification and other alternatives with a new station at Headbolt Lane to serve the Northwood area of Kirkby. The document on page 37 states two trials of electric 3rd rail/battery trains will be undertaken in 2020, this is one of the \"alternatives\".  <ref>http://moderngov.merseytravel.uk.net/documents/s21686/Enc.%201%20for%20Updated%20Long%20term%20Rail%20Strategy.pdf</ref>\n\nLancashire County Coucil approved a plan in May 2019 to commission an outline business case into reopening the station which will be presented to the government.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Faulkner |first1=Paul |title=Plans for Skelmersdale train station move one step closer |url=https://www.lancs.live/news/lancashire-news/plans-skelmersdale-train-station-move-16294321 |accessdate=31 August 2019 |work=Lancs Live |date=17 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{citation |last=James |first=David |title=Lancashire's Lost Railways |publisher=Stenlake Publishing |year=2004 |isbn=1 84033 288 3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.subbrit.org.uk/sb-sites/stations/s/skelmersdale/index.shtml Description via ''Disused Stations UK'']\n* [http://www.skemheritage.org.uk/ackerley/railway.htm The coming of the railway]\n* [http://www.npemap.org.uk/tiles/map.html#346,405,1 The station on an old O.S. Map via ''npemaps'']\n\n{{Disused Rail Start}}\n{{Rail line\n|previous=[[Westhead Halt railway station|Westhead Halt]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> \n|next=[[White Moss Level Crossing railway station|White Moss Level Crossing Halt]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> \n|route=[[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]]<br><small>[[Skelmersdale branch]]</small> \n|col={{LYR colour}} }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Merseyrail Northern Line}}\n{{Closed stations Lancashire}}\n{{Proposed rail infrastructure projects in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in the Borough of West Lancashire]]\n[[Category:Former Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1858]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1956]]\n[[Category:Proposed railway stations in England]]\n[[Category:Skelmersdale]]\n", "name_user": "Isufferfromlag", "label": "safe", "comment": "added information the the history section with my source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skelmersdale_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "Geoff Simons", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n'''Geoffrey Leslie Simons''' (23 November 1939 \u2013 31 August 2011), best known as '''Geoff L. Simons''' was a British freelance writer. In the 1980s, he was chief editor at the [[National Computing Centre]] in Manchester. A prolific author of non-fiction, he wrote books about sex, [[computers]] and politics, particularly the history of the Middle East.\n\n==Career==\nGeoff Simons was born in [[Stockport]], and lived in or around [[Greater Manchester]] throughout his life. He worked as an Information Officer at several companies, as well as working as a technical author and editor.<ref name=\"Simons1984\">{{cite book|last=Simons|first=Geoff|title=Are Computers Alive?: Evolution and New Life Forms|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yPAaAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=18 October 2012|year=1984|publisher=Corgi Books|isbn=978-0-552-99093-6|page=3}}</ref> He wrote hardware and software manuals at [[Ferranti]] and [[International Computers Limited|ICL]]. As Chief Editor at the NCC, he established ''Computer Journal Abstracts'' and wrote summaries for over 20,000 computer articles.<ref name=\"Simons1982\">{{cite book|last=Simons|first=G. L.|title=Computers in engineering and manufacture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dtftAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=18 October 2012|year=1982|publisher=NCC Publications|isbn=978-0-85012-347-0|page=2}}</ref>\n\nSimons was a critic of [[US foreign policy]], regarding [[sanctions against Iraq]] in the 1990s as [[genocide]],<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/letter-iraqis-killed-by-sanctions-1243165.html Letter: Iraqis killed by sanctions], ''[[The Independent]]'', 1 August 1997</ref> and the United States as \"a [[plutocracy]] that shapes foreign policy in the cynical calculation of elitist commercial advantage\".<ref>[http://www.worlddialogue.org/print.php?id=123 Letters] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004233735/http://www.worlddialogue.org/print.php?id=123 |date=4 October 2013 }}, ''Global Dialogue'', Vol. 2, No. 4 (Autumn 2000)</ref> In later life he was a frequent correspondent to newspapers, seeing his letters published in ''[[The Times]]'',<ref>Letters to the editor of ''The Times'', 23 February 2004, 13 March 2004, 19 September 2005.</ref> the ''[[Sunday Times]]'',<ref>Letter to the editor of the ''Sunday Times'', 7 September 2003.</ref> ''[[The Independent]]'',<ref>Letters to the editor of ''The Independent'', 18 October 1993, 19 January 1996, 7 February 1997, 1 August 1997, 14 August 1997, 2 September 1997, 15 October 1998, 14 January 2002, 27 March 2002, 6 April 2002, 5 September 2002, 21 August 2003.</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>Letters to the editor of ''The Guardian'', 6 July 1994, 8 January 2008, 3 March 2009, 7 April 2009, 25 April 2009, 19 August 2009, 4 September 2009, 21 September 2009, 23 July 2010, 27 July 2010, 23 April 2011, 3 May 2011.</ref> the ''[[New Statesman]]'',<ref>Letters to the editor of the ''New Statesman'', 28 February 2005, 6 June 2005, 19 September 2005, 7 November 2005, 6 February 2006, 21 December 2009, 4 January 2010, 18 February 2010.</ref> and the ''[[Morning Star (UK newspaper)|Morning Star]]''.<ref>Letters to the editor of the ''Morning Star'', 7 January 2006, 22 March 2006, 6 April 2006.</ref> He died on 31 August 2011. He was survived by his widow, Christine, children, grandchildren and great-granddaughter.<ref>Guy Oten, [http://www.meetup.com/Greater-Manchester-Humanists/messages/boards/thread/15444262 Geoff Simons], 2 September 2011</ref>\n\n==Skepticism==\n\nSimons was an [[atheism|atheist]] and [[Skepticism|skeptic]]. He was a member of Greater Manchester Humanists. In his book ''Is God a Programmer?'', he defended atheism and criticized the [[Teleological argument|argument from design]].\n\n==Works==\n* ''Sex in the modern world'', 1970.\n* ''A history of sex'', 1970.\n* ''Sex tomorrow'', 1971.\n* ''Does sex make you feel guilty?'', 1972.\n* ''Pornography without prejudice: a reply to objectors'', 1972.\n* ''A place for pleasure: the history of the brothel'', 1973.\n* ''The witchcraft world'', 1974.\n* ''The Simons book of sexual records'', 1975.\n* ''Introducing microprocessors'', 1979.\n* ''Robots in industry'', 1980.\n* ''The uses of microprocessors'', 1980.\n* ''Introducing word processing'', 1981.\n* ''Women in computing'', 1981.\n* ''The illustrated book of sexual records'', 1982. Second ed., 1985.\n* ''Privacy in the computer age'', 1982.\n* ''Computers in engineering and manufacture'', 1982.\n* ''The book of world sexual records'', 1983.\n* ''Sex and superstition'', 1983.\n* ''Are computers alive? Evolution and new life forms'', 1983.\n* ''Automating your office'', 1984.\n* ''Computer bits and pieces: a compendium of curiosities'', 1984.\n* ''Expert systems and micros'', 1985.\n* ''Towards fifth-generation computers'', 1986.\n* ''Is man a robot'', 1986.\n* ''Introducing artificial intelligence'', 1984.\n* ''The biology of computer life: survival, emotion and free will'', 1985.\n* ''Silicon shock: the menace of the computer invasion'', 1985.\n* (with R. T. Doswell) ''Fraud and abuse of IT systems'', 1986.\n* ''Eco-computer: the impact of global intelligence'', 1987.\n* ''What is software engineering?'', 1987.\n* ''Introducing software engineering'', 1987.\n* ''Evolution of the intelligent machine: a popular history of AI'', 1988.\n* ''Is God a programmer?: religion in the computer age'', 1988.\n* ''Silicon psychosis: derangement in the global network'', 1989.\n* ''Viruses, bugs and star wars: the hazards of unsafe computing'', 1989.\n* ''Robots: the quest for living machines'', . New ed., 1994.\n* ''Robots and robotics'', 1992.\n* ''Libya: the struggle for survival'', 1993. 2nd ed. (with foreword by [[Tam Dalyell]]), 1996.\n* ''Iraq: from Sumer to Saddam'', 1994. Foreword by [[Tony Benn]]. 2nd ed., 1996. 3rd ed., 2003.\n* ''The United Nations: a chronology of conflict'', 1994.\n* ''Korea: the search for sovereignty'', 1995, Reprinted with foreword by [[Tony Benn]], 1999.\n* ''UN malaise: power, problems, and realpolitik'', 1995.\n* ''Cuba: from conqistador to Castro'', 1996.\n* ''The scourging of Iraq : sanctions, law, and natural justice'', 1996. 2nd ed., 1998.\n* ''Vietnam syndrome: impact on US foreign policy'', 1998. Foreword by [[Tony Benn]].\n* ''Saudi Arabia: the shape of a client feudalism'', 1998.\n* ''Iraq \u2013 primus inter pariahs: A crisis chronology'', 1999.\n* ''Imposing legal sanctions: legal remedy or genocidal tool?'', 1999.\n* ''Indonesia: the long oppression'', 1999.\n* ''UN Reform: Addressing the Reality of American Power', ''Global Dialogue'', Vol. 2., No. 2 (Spring 2000)\n* ''Targeting Iraq: sanctions and bombing in US policy'', 2002.\n* ''Future Iraq: US policy in reshaping the Middle East'', 2003.\n* ''Colombia: a brutal history'', 2004.\n* ''Libya and the West: from independence to Lockerbie'', 2004. Foreword by [[Tony Benn]].\n* ''Iraq endgame?: surge, suffering and the politics of denial'', 2008.\n* ''Time to be rational: Darwin, demons and sex.'', 2009.\n* ''Nuclear nightmares'', 2009.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simons, Geoff}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:Critics of creationism]]\n[[Category:English atheists]]\n[[Category:English book editors]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English sceptics]]\n[[Category:Historians of the Middle East]]\n[[Category:Letter writers]]\n[[Category:People from Stockport]]\n[[Category:Relationships and sexuality writers]]\n[[Category:Technical writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n'''Geoffrey Leslie Simons''' (23 November 1939 \u2013 31 August 2011), best known as '''Geoff L. Simons''' was a British freelance writer. In the 1980s, he was chief editor at the [[National Computing Centre]] in Manchester. A prolific author of non-fiction, he wrote books about sex, [[computers]] and politics, particularly the history of the Middle East.\n\n==Career==\nGeoff Simons was born in [[Stockport]], and lived in or around [[Greater Manchester]] throughout his life. He worked as an Information Officer at several companies, as well as working as a technical author and editor.<ref name=\"Simons1984\">{{cite book|last=Simons|first=Geoff|title=Are Computers Alive?: Evolution and New Life Forms|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yPAaAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=18 October 2012|year=1984|publisher=Corgi Books|isbn=978-0-552-99093-6|page=3}}</ref> He wrote hardware and software manuals at [[Ferranti]] and [[International Computers Limited|ICL]]. As Chief Editor at the NCC, he established ''Computer Journal Abstracts'' and wrote summaries for over 20,000 computer articles.<ref name=\"Simons1982\">{{cite book|last=Simons|first=G. L.|title=Computers in engineering and manufacture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dtftAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=18 October 2012|year=1982|publisher=NCC Publications|isbn=978-0-85012-347-0|page=2}}</ref>\n\nSimons was a critic of [[US foreign policy]], regarding [[sanctions against Iraq]] in the 1990s as [[genocide]],<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/letter-iraqis-killed-by-sanctions-1243165.html Letter: Iraqis killed by sanctions], ''[[The Independent]]'', 1 August 1997</ref> and the United States as \"a [[plutocracy]] that shapes foreign policy in the cynical calculation of elitist commercial advantage\".<ref>[http://www.worlddialogue.org/print.php?id=123 Letters] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004233735/http://www.worlddialogue.org/print.php?id=123 |date=4 October 2013 }}, ''Global Dialogue'', Vol. 2, No. 4 (Autumn 2000)</ref> In later life he was a frequent correspondent to newspapers, seeing his letters published in ''[[The Times]]'',<ref>Letters to the editor of ''The Times'', 23 February 2004, 13 March 2004, 19 September 2005.</ref> the ''[[Sunday Times]]'',<ref>Letter to the editor of the ''Sunday Times'', 7 September 2003.</ref> ''[[The Independent]]'',<ref>Letters to the editor of ''The Independent'', 18 October 1993, 19 January 1996, 7 February 1997, 1 August 1997, 14 August 1997, 2 September 1997, 15 October 1998, 14 January 2002, 27 March 2002, 6 April 2002, 5 September 2002, 21 August 2003.</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>Letters to the editor of ''The Guardian'', 6 July 1994, 8 January 2008, 3 March 2009, 7 April 2009, 25 April 2009, 19 August 2009, 4 September 2009, 21 September 2009, 23 July 2010, 27 July 2010, 23 April 2011, 3 May 2011.</ref> the ''[[New Statesman]]'',<ref>Letters to the editor of the ''New Statesman'', 28 February 2005, 6 June 2005, 19 September 2005, 7 November 2005, 6 February 2006, 21 December 2009, 4 January 2010, 18 February 2010.</ref> and the ''[[Morning Star (UK newspaper)|Morning Star]]''.<ref>Letters to the editor of the ''Morning Star'', 7 January 2006, 22 March 2006, 6 April 2006.</ref> He died on 31 August 2011. He was survived by his widow, Christine, children, grandchildren and great-granddaughter.<ref>Guy Oten, [http://www.meetup.com/Greater-Manchester-Humanists/messages/boards/thread/15444262 Geoff Simons], 2 September 2011</ref>\n\n==Skepticism==\n\nSimons was an [[atheism|atheist]] and [[Skepticism|skeptic]]. He was a member of Greater Manchester Humanists. In his book ''Is God a Programmer?'', he defended atheism and criticized the [[Teleological argument|argument from design]].\n\n==Works==\n* ''Sex in the modern world'', 1970.\n* ''A history of sex'', 1970.\n* ''Sex tomorrow'', 1971.\n* ''Does sex make you feel guilty?'', 1972.\n* ''Pornography without prejudice: a reply to objectors'', 1972.\n* ''A place for pleasure: the history of the brothel'', 1973.\n* ''The witchcraft world'', 1974.\n* ''The Simons book of sexual records'', 1975.\n* ''Introducing microprocessors'', 1979.\n* ''Robots in industry'', 1980.\n* ''The uses 